{"title_page": "Chestnut-rumped heathwren", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Chestnut-rumped heathwren\n| image = Chestnut- Rumped Heathwren small fx.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite journal | author =BirdLife International | title = ''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'' | journal = [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume=2012 | page =e.T22704604A39302518  | year =2012 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012-1.RLTS.T22704604A39302518.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Hylacola\n| species = pyrrhopygia\n| authority = ([[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]] & [[Thomas Horsfield|Horsfield]], 1827)\n| synonyms = *''Calamanthus pyrrhopygia pyrrhopygia'' <small>Christidis and Boles (2008)</small>\n*''Hylacola pyrrhopygius pyrrhopygius'' <small>Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993)</small>}}\nThe '''chestnut-rumped heathwren''' (''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]].\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to temperate and subtropical forests of [[Australia]].\n\n==Description==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren is a small bushland bird with an olive-brown back, reddish-brown rump, and streaked brown-on-white chest. There is a terminal grey band on the tail. Both sexes have a prominent white eyebrow; eyes are yellow, while bill, legs, and feet are grey.<ref name=mdahlem>{{cite web|title=Chestnut-rumped Heathwren|url=http://www.mdahlem.net/birds/17/chrhwren.php|website=Mdahlem.net}}</ref> It measures {{convert|14|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name = \"Campbell\"/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren occurs in southeastern Australia through eastern New South Wales, Victoria, and southeast South Australia.<ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://birdata.birdlife.org.au/explore#map=-27.8587126_141.4881509_5&species_id=498|title=birdata map:chestnut-rumped heathwren|accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nThe species is currently classified as [[least-concern species|Least Concern]] by the [[IUCN]]. However, it is nationally listed as Endangered in South Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/sharedassets/public/plants_and_animals/threatened_species/pa-fact-chestnutrumpedheathwrenmountloftyranges.pdf|publisher=Natural Resources: Adelaide and Mt Lofty Ranges|title=Threatened Species Profile:Chestnut-rumped Heathwren (Mount Lofty Ranges)}}</ref> and Vulnerable in Victoria.,<ref name=\"DSE200\">{{cite book | author = Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment | title = Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2007 | publisher = Department of Sustainability and Environment | year = 2007 | location = East Melbourne, Victoria | pages = 15 | url = | isbn = 978-1-74208-039-0 }}</ref> with continued [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[loss of habitat]] and predation by [[introduced species|introduced]] predators being regarded as the main pressures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs =\n<ref name = \"Campbell\">{{cite book | title = Birds of Australia: A Photographic Guide | first = Iain | last = Campbell | first2 = Sam | last2 = Woods | first3 = Nick | last3 = Leseberg | year = 2015 | location = Princeton, NJ, US | publisher = Princeton University Press | page = 248 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wFMCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA248 | isbn = 978-0-691-15727-6}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075266}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:heathwren, chestnut-rumped}}\n[[Category:Hylacola|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1827|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Chestnut-rumped heathwren\n| image = Chestnut- Rumped Heathwren small fx.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite journal | author =BirdLife International | title = ''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'' | journal = [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume=2012 | page =e.T22704604A39302518  | year =2012 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012-1.RLTS.T22704604A39302518.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Hylacola\n| species = pyrrhopygia\n| authority = ([[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]] & [[Thomas Horsfield|Horsfield]], 1827)\n| synonyms = *''Calamanthus pyrrhopygia pyrrhopygia'' <small>Christidis and Boles (2008)</small>\n*''Hylacola pyrrhopygius pyrrhopygius'' <small>Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993)</small>}}\nThe '''chestnut-rumped heathwren''' (''Hylacola pyrrhopygia'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]].\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to temperate and subtropical forests of [[Australia]].\n\n==Description==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren is a small bushland bird with an olive-brown back, reddish-brown rump, and streaked brown-on-white chest. There is a terminal grey band on the tail. Both sexes have a prominent white eyebrow; eyes are yellow, while bill, legs, and feet are grey.<ref name=mdahlem>{{cite web|title=Chestnut-rumped Heathwren|url=http://www.mdahlem.net/birds/17/chrhwren.php|website=Mdahlem.net}}</ref> It measures {{convert|14|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name = \"Campbell\"/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe chestnut-rumped heathwren occurs in southeastern Australia through eastern New South Wales, Victoria, and southeast South Australia.<ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field Guide to Australian Birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://birdata.birdlife.org.au/explore#map=-27.8587126_141.4881509_5&species_id=498|title=birdata map:chestnut-rumped heathwren|accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nThe species is currently classified as [[least-concern species|Least Concern]] by the [[IUCN]]. However, it is nationally listed as Endangered in South Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/sharedassets/public/plants_and_animals/threatened_species/pa-fact-chestnutrumpedheathwrenmountloftyranges.pdf|publisher=Natural Resources: Adelaide and Mt Lofty Ranges|title=Threatened Species Profile:Chestnut-rumped Heathwren (Mount Lofty Ranges)}}</ref> and Vulnerable in Victoria.,<ref name=\"DSE200\">{{cite book | author = Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment | title = Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2007 | publisher = Department of Sustainability and Environment | year = 2007 | location = East Melbourne, Victoria | pages = 15 | url = | isbn = 978-1-74208-039-0 }}</ref> with continued [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[loss of habitat]] and predation by [[introduced species|introduced]] predators being regarded as the main pressures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs =\n<ref name = \"Campbell\">{{cite book | title = Birds of Australia: A Photographic Guide | first = Iain | last = Campbell | first2 = Sam | last2 = Woods | first3 = Nick | last3 = Leseberg | year = 2015 | location = Princeton, NJ, US | publisher = Princeton University Press | page = 248 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wFMCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA248 | isbn = 978-0-691-15727-6}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075266}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:heathwren, chestnut-rumped}}\n[[Category:Hylacola|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1827|chestnut-rumped heathwren]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution and habitat:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chestnut-rumped_heathwren"}
{"title_page": "Coat of arms of Sofia", "text_new": "{{Infobox coat of arms\n | name             = Coat of arms of Sofia\n | image            = BG Sofia coa.svg\n | image_width      = 150\n | middle           = \n | middle_width     = \n | lesser           = \n | lesser_width     = \n | armiger          = Government of the city of [[Sofia]]\n | year_adopted     = 1928\n | shield           = \n | crest            = A three-tower [[mural crown]]\n | supporters       = None\n | motto            = (1911\u20131974; 1991\u2013)<br>'''\u0420\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0463\u0435'''<br>([[Reforms of Bulgarian orthography|Bulgarian with pre-1945 orthography]])<br><br>(1974\u20131991)<br>'''\u0420\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0435''' <br>([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]])<br><br> \"Ever Growing, Never Aging\"\n | other_elements   = \n | earlier_versions = \n | use              = \n}}\n\nThe '''[[coat of arms]] of [[Sofia]]''' consists of a shield divided into four. The image of the [[Saint Sofia Church, Sofia|Church of St. Sophia]] which gave the name to the city takes up the upper left quarter (as seen from behind the shield) and a humanized picture of the ancient town of [[Serdica]] taken from an antique coin is located to the right (again, heraldry [[dexter and sinister|reverses right and left]] as it is from the point of view of someone holding the shield from behind). At lower left is a golden [[baldachin]] and a statue of [[Apollo Medicus]] representing the [[mineral spring]]s around the city, while the lower right quarter is reserved for [[Vitosha]], the mountain at the foot of which Sofia is located. \n\nIn the middle is another, smaller shield ([[inescutcheon]]), with a lion rampant, a traditional [[Bulgaria]]n symbol. A [[mural crown]] tops the larger shield. At the bottom is the city motto, \"\u0420\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0435\" \u2013 ''Raste, no ne staree'' (\"Ever Growing, Never Aging\").<ref>The last word is written in the old style, with the letter [[Yat|\u0462 (yat)]].</ref>'''\n\n==History==\nThe coat of arms was created for the [[Paris]] [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle]] in 1900 by a team of three noted Bulgarian artists and specialists \u2013 Haralampi Tachev, [[Ivan Mrkvi\u010dka]] and [[V\u00e1clav Dobrusk\u00fd]], as the city was required by the executive committee to submit a symbol in order to take part. The then-[[List of Bulgarian monarchs|Knyaz]] [[Ferdinand of Bulgaria|Ferdinand]] approved the coat of arms and it was sent to Paris.\n\nChanges were made to the original image of the coat of arms in the following years. The motto was first added in 1911 by Haralampi Tachev, who also gave it a final touch by adding a band with the motto and [[Bay Laurel|laurel]] twigs in 1928. A simplified version was suggested by Boris Angelushev in the 1940s, with Ivan Radoev adding a five-pointed star and additionally stylizing the coat of arms in 1974. The 1928 edition of Haralampi Tachev returned into official use after the [[History of Democratic Bulgaria|democratic changes]].\n\n== Gallery==\n<gallery>\nCoat of arms of Sofia (1900-1911).svg|1900-1911\nCoat of arms of Sofia (1911-1928).svg|1911-1928\nBG Sofia coa.svg|1928-1974\nCoat of arms of Sofia (1974-1991).svg|1974-1991\nBG Sofia coa.svg|1991\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{portal|Heraldry|Bulgaria}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sofia.bg/template4.asp?ime=GERB%7D&title=%CE%E1%F9%E0%20%E0%E4%EC%E8%ED%E8%F1%F2%F0%E0%F6%E8%FF&fail=oa&update=noem The act restoring the original coat of arms in 1991]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20060524035517/http://www.sofia.bg/history.asp?lines=41&nxt=1&update=all The Birth of the Coat of Arms]'', excerpt from a publication by Haralampi Tachev. Sofia municipal website, accessed 5 April 2006.\n\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Municipal coats of arms in Bulgaria|Sofia]]\n[[Category:Culture in Sofia]]\n[[Category:History of Sofia]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with buildings|Sofia]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with mountains|Sofia]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with lions|Sofia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox coat of arms\n | name             = Coat of arms of Sofia\n | image            = BG Sofia coa.svg\n | image_width      = 150\n | middle           = \n | middle_width     = \n | lesser           = \n | lesser_width     = \n | armiger          = Government of the city of [[Sofia]]\n | year_adopted     = 1928\n | shield           = \n | crest            = A three-tower [[mural crown]]\n | supporters       = None\n | motto            = (1911\u20131974; 1991\u2013)<br>'''\u0420\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0463\u0435'''<br>([[Reforms of Bulgarian orthography|Bulgarian with pre-1945 orthography]])<br><br>(1974\u20131991)<br>'''\u0420\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0435''' <br>([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]])<br><br> \"Ever Growing, Never Aging\"\n | other_elements   = \n | earlier_versions = \n | use              = \n}}\n\nThe '''[[coat of arms]] of [[Sofia]]''' consists of a shield divided into four. The image of the [[Saint Sofia Church, Sofia|Church of St. Sophia]] which gave the name to the city takes up the upper left quarter (as seen from behind the shield) and a humanized picture of the ancient town of [[Serdica]] taken from an antique coin is located to the right (again, heraldry [[dexter and sinister|reverses right and left]] as it is from the point of view of someone holding the shield from behind). At lower left is a golden [[baldachin]] and a statue of [[Apollo Medicus]] representing the [[mineral spring]]s around the city, while the lower right quarter is reserved for [[Vitosha]], the mountain at the foot of which Sofia is located. \n\nIn the middle is another, smaller shield ([[inescutcheon]]), with a lion rampant, a traditional [[Bulgaria]]n symbol. A [[mural crown]] tops the larger shield, an element typically reserved for city coat of arms. At the bottom is the city motto, \"\u0420\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0435\" \u2013 ''Raste, no ne staree'' (\"Ever Growing, Never Aging\").<ref>The last word is written in the old style, with the letter [[Yat|\u0462 (yat)]].</ref>'''\n\n==History==\nThe coat of arms was created for the [[Paris]] [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle]] in 1900 by a team of three noted Bulgarian artists and specialists \u2013 Haralampi Tachev, [[Ivan Mrkvi\u010dka]] and [[V\u00e1clav Dobrusk\u00fd]], as the city was required by the executive committee to submit a symbol in order to take part. The then-[[List of Bulgarian monarchs|Knyaz]] [[Ferdinand of Bulgaria|Ferdinand]] approved the coat of arms and it was sent to Paris.\n\nChanges were made to the original image of the coat of arms in the following years. The motto was first added in 1911 by Haralampi Tachev, who also gave it a final touch by adding a band with the motto and [[Bay Laurel|laurel]] twigs in 1928. A simplified version was suggested by Boris Angelushev in the 1940s, with Ivan Radoev adding a five-pointed star and additionally stylizing the coat of arms in 1974. The 1928 edition of Haralampi Tachev returned into official use after the [[History of Democratic Bulgaria|democratic changes]].\n\n== Gallery==\n<gallery>\nCoat of arms of Sofia (1900-1911).svg|1900-1911\nCoat of arms of Sofia (1911-1928).svg|1911-1928\nBG Sofia coa.svg|1928-1974\nCoat of arms of Sofia (1974-1991).svg|1974-1991\nBG Sofia coa.svg|1991\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{portal|Heraldry|Bulgaria}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sofia.bg/template4.asp?ime=GERB%7D&title=%CE%E1%F9%E0%20%E0%E4%EC%E8%ED%E8%F1%F2%F0%E0%F6%E8%FF&fail=oa&update=noem The act restoring the original coat of arms in 1991]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20060524035517/http://www.sofia.bg/history.asp?lines=41&nxt=1&update=all The Birth of the Coat of Arms]'', excerpt from a publication by Haralampi Tachev. Sofia municipal website, accessed 5 April 2006.\n\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Municipal coats of arms in Bulgaria|Sofia]]\n[[Category:Culture in Sofia]]\n[[Category:History of Sofia]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with buildings|Sofia]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with mountains|Sofia]]\n[[Category:Coats of arms with lions|Sofia]]\n", "name_user": "Vasilken", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Sofia"}
{"title_page": "Michelle Thomson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Michelle Thomson\n|office       = [[Scottish National Party#Ministers and spokespeople|SNP Spokesperson]] for [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Business, Innovation and Skills]]\n|term_start   = 20 May 2015\n|term_end     = 30 September 2015\n|predecessor  = Position established\n|successor    = [[Hannah Bardell]]\n|office1      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Edinburgh West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh West]]\n|term_start1  = 8 May 2015\n|term_end1    = 3 May 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Mike Crockart]]\n|successor1   = [[Christine Jardine]]\n|birth_name   = Michelle Rhonda Perks \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1965|3|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bearsden]], Scotland, UK\n|party        = [[Scottish National Party]]<br />{{small|(1981\u20132015, 2018\u2013)}}<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2015\u201317)}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland|Royal Scottish Academy of<br />Music and Drama]]\n}}\n'''Michelle Rhonda Thomson''' (born 11 March 1965) is a Scottish businesswoman and former [[politician]]. She is the co-founder of Momentous Change Ltd,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://momentouschangeltd.co.uk/|title=Momentous Change Ltd - Home|website=momentouschangeltd.co.uk}}</ref> a consultancy she set up with Professor [[Roger Mullin]] in 2017 to help organisations manage change. In 2018, Momentous Change published its first report, Brexit and Scottish Business.<ref>http://momentouschangeltd.co.uk/images/news/2018/FINAL_Brexit_and_Scottish_Business_report.pdf</ref>\n\nPrior to this, Thomson was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Edinburgh West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh West]] from May 2015 until May 2017. She served as the SNP Business, Innovation and Skills spokesperson in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] until her resignation of the party whip in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/2334493|title=List of Members returned to Parliament at the General Election 2015 Scotland|work=[[The Edinburgh Gazette]]|date=15 May 2015|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News\"/> She was also a member of the Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) Committee from 2015 to 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/business-energy-industrial-strategy/news-parliament-2015/2015-membership/|title=Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Committee membership at the end of Parliament 2015-17 - News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nSince stepping down from the House of Commons in 2017, she has been appointed as Ambassador for the All Party Parliamentary Group for Fair Business Banking.<ref>http://www.appgbanking.org.uk/about-us/</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nThomson graduated from the [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland|Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] in 1985.\n\nThomson initially worked as a professional musician and then completed a post graduate diploma in [[Information technology]] (IT).<ref name=\"Who's Who 2017\">{{cite web|title=THOMSON, Michelle Rhonda|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U284018|website=Who's Who 2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=8 December 2016|date=November 2016}}</ref> She worked in Financial Services for [[Standard Life]] and the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] for over 23 years in a variety of senior roles delivering IT and business change. In 2009 she set up her own small business in property.<ref name=\"EN 9May2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/midlothian-elects-owen-thompson-as-council-leader-1-3194409 |title=Midlothian elects Owen Thompson as council leader |author=<!-- Staff writer/no by-line --> |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=11 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518094942/http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/midlothian-elects-owen-thompson-as-council-leader-1-3194409 |archive-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Indy\">{{cite news|last1=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/comment/the-city-should-not-dismiss-the-snp-as-a-single-issue-party-10193981.html|title=The City should not dismiss the SNP as a single issue party|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Momentous Change Ltd==\nThomson established Momentous Change Ltd in 2017 with co-founder Professor Roger Mullin. Momentous Change is a niche consultancy providing support to businesses through economic management and operational change. The firm self-funded research involving 236 senior Scottish business leaders across industry to establish their concerns over Brexit. The final report was published in February 2018. Its principal findings and recommendations included the need for a new skills strategy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16034112.uk-brexit-stance-is-against-the-interest-of-scottish-business/|title=UK Brexit stance is 'against' the interest of Scottish business|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref> and greater financial and practical support from government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/16038858.scottish-businesses-call-for-urgent-clarity-on-which-eu-powers-will-be-devolved-to-holyrood/|title=Scottish businesses call for 'urgent clarity' on which EU powers will be devolved to Holyrood|website=The National}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Thomson was a co-author of a Momentous Change Ltd report into the prospects for establishing a Scottish Stock Exchange.<ref>http://www.momentouschangeltd.co.uk/images/news/2018/Final-Report---Stock-Exchange.pdf</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nThomson joined the Scottish National Party at the age of sixteen in 1981.<ref name=\"Indy\"/> She became prominent politically during the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum campaign]], with the \"Yes\" campaign. She was elected as the Member of Parliament for Edinburgh West in 2015 with a majority of 3,210 votes and a 39% share of the vote; with a swing of 25.8% from Liberal Democrat to SNP.\n\nAs part of her role on the BEIS committee, Thomson was one of the members of the joint committee inquiries into the collapse of [[British Home Stores|BHS]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/work-and-pensions-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/bhs-inquiry-16-17/|title=BHS inquiry|website=UK Parliament|access-date=5 December 2016}}</ref> into the working practices of Sports Direct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/09/mike-ashley-asked-to-explain-camera-mps-sports-direct-visit-warehouse|title=Mike Ashley asked to explain 'secret filming' of MPs' Sports Direct visit|first=Sean|last=Farrell|date=9 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/07/six-mps-surprise-visit-sports-direct-shirebrook-warehouse|title=Sports Direct accused of secretly recording MPs during warehouse visit|first=Simon|last=Goodley|date=7 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Sunday Post]]'' described her as one of the SNP MPs to watch in the new parliament.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sundaypost.com/news-views/politics/out-with-the-old-and-in-with-the-new-12-snp-mps-to-watch-1.873640 | title=Out with the old and in with the new \u2013 12 SNP MPs to watch | first=James | last=Millar |work=[[Sunday Post]]| date=9 May 2015 | accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/scottish-mps-in-westminster-the-full-list-of-the-snp-parliamentarians-10234893.html | title=Scottish MPs in Westminster: The full list of the SNP parliamentarians | work=[[The Independent]] | first=Ben | last=Tufft | date=8 May 2015 | accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> [[The National (Scotland)|''The National'']] described Thomson as \"a breath of fresh air\" in light of her broad-based life experience.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.scot/politics/meet-your-new-scottish-mps-34-michelle-thomson-edinburgh-west.4904|title=Meet your new Scottish MPs: #34 Michelle Thomson, Edinburgh West|work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]]|location=Scotland|date=7 July 2015|last=Hannan|first=Martin}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, in a [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] debate focused on UN International Day For The Elimination Of Violence Against Women, Thomson described the impact of having been raped at the age of fourteen years old, highlighting the conditions of silence and shame that prevent rape from being discussed or reported.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-38250541|title=Michelle Thomson MP recalls being raped at age of 14|publisher=BBC News|date=8 December 2016|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThomson was sitting as an independent MP when the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 snap general election]] was called on 18 April 2017. The SNP's national executive met four days later and ruled that they would not endorse her as an SNP candidate. She did not stand as an independent at that election, issuing a statement that noted, \"even in political parties the concept of natural justice must apply, as must the need for defined processes that are applied fairly, rigorously and transparently. I would advise the SNP to employ the services of an external body to help them develop a process as soon as possible.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/michelle-thomson-to-step-down-as-mp-after-snp-ruling-1-4426630 |title=Michelle Thomson to step down as MP after SNP ruling |first=Russell |last=Jackson |work=The Scotsman |date=22 April 2017 |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Property allegations===\nIn September 2015, Thomson was accused by an article in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' of having built her buy-to-let property portfolio by buying homes for below-market prices.<ref>{{cite news |last=Macaskill |first=Mark |last2=Ungoed-Thomas |first2=Jon |date=20 September 2015 |title=SNP MP snaps up homes of struggling families |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/scotland/article1609551.ece |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=21 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn late-September 2015, [[Police Scotland]] announced it had launched an inquiry into \"alleged irregularities\" related to the property transactions which had seen her solicitor struck off.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sanderson |first=Daniel |date=29 September 2015 |title=Police launch inquiry into property deals involving SNP MP |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13791520.Police_launch_into_inquiry_into_property_deals_involving_SNP_MP/ |newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |access-date=29 September 2015 }}</ref> The same day the SNP issued a statement on behalf of Thomson, announcing that she had decided to withdraw herself from the party whip whilst the investigation was ongoing. In resigning the whip, Thomson also lost her SNP membership and her role as the SNP's Business, Innovation and Skills spokesperson at Westminster.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |date=29 September 2015 |title=Probe over property deals on behalf of Michelle Thomson MP |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-34395392 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=29 September 2015 }}</ref> Thomson subsequently claimed she had been forced to resign the whip.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/ex-snp-mp-michelle-thomson-urges-nicola-sturgeon-to-apologise-to-her-after-being-cleared-in-mortgage-fraud-probe/|title=Ex-SNP MP Michelle Thomson urges Nicola Sturgeon to apologise to her after being cleared in mortgage fraud probe|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15456354.michelle-thomson-breaks-her-silence-my-two-years-of-hell/|title=Michelle Thomson breaks her silence: 'My two years of hell'|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-40842247|title=Scotland's papers: 'My two years of hell'|date=6 August 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nEight months after the story broke, Thomson issued a press statement noting that there had been no contact with her from [[Police Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14522314.suspended-snp-mp-reveals-lack-of-police-contact-amid-property-firm-investigation/|title=Suspended SNP MP reveals lack of police contact amid property firm investigation|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the investigation was dropped.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40788469|title=Michelle Thomson: Fraud case against former SNP MP dropped|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> Former Scottish Government Minister Kenny MacAskill said the SNP had lessons to learn over their handling of her case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/kenny-macaskill-lessons-to-be-learned-from-michelle-thomson-case-1-4526930|title=Kenny MacAskill: Lessons to be learned from Michelle Thomson case|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref> Former First Minister Alex Salmond was also quoted as saying how badly Thomson had been treated by the media and the SNP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40910096|title=Salmond criticises SNP over Thomson|date=12 August 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nShe rejoined the SNP in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/former-mp-michelle-thomson-has-rejoined-the-snp-1-4857567|title=Former MP Michelle Thomson has rejoined the SNP|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\"Scottish Business and International Trade - Perceptions of the Scottish Business Diaspora\", Momentous Change Ltd, January 2020.\n\n\"Why Banks Must Change\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://internationalbanker.com/banking/why-banks-must-change/|title=Why Banks Must Change|date=5 September 2018|website=International Banker}}</ref> International Banker, 5 September 2018. Retrieved 7 September 2018. [https://internationalbanker.com/banking/why-banks-must-change/ Why Banks Must Change]\n\n\"A Stock Exchange for Scotland: Early background research\", Momentous Change Ltd, November 2018.\n\n\"The Illusion Of Stability Gives Way To The Reality Of Change In Capital Markets - Introducing Scotland's New Stock Exchange\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://internationalbanker.com/brokerage/the-illusion-of-stability-gives-way-to-the-reality-of-change-in-capital-markets-introducing-scotlands-new-stock-exchange/|title=The Illusion Of Stability Gives Way To The Reality Of Change In Capital Markets - Introducing Scotland's New Stock |date=11 June 2019|website=International Banker}}</ref> International Banker, 11 June 2019. Retrieved 30 July 2019. [https://internationalbanker.com/brokerage/the-illusion-of-stability-gives-way-to-the-reality-of-change-in-capital-markets-introducing-scotlands-new-stock-exchange/ The Illusion of Stability Gives Way to the Reality of Change in Capital Markets: Introducing Scotland\u2019s New Stock Exchange]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150515075813/http://www.snp.org/people/michelle-thomson Profile] on [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] website\n* {{twitter | michellethomson | Michelle Thomson }}\n{{UK MP links\n| parliament   = michelle-thomson/4422\n| hansard      = \n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Michelle_Thomson&mpc=Edinburgh_West&house=commons\n| theywork     = 25352/michelle_thomson/edinburgh_west\n| record       = \n| bbc          = 137579.stm\n| journalisted =\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Crockart]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Edinburgh West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh West]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Christine Jardine]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Former SNP MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomson, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Edinburgh constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Bearsden]]\n[[Category:Rape in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Royal Bank of Scotland people]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Michelle Thomson\n|office       = [[Scottish National Party#Ministers and spokespeople|SNP Spokesperson]] for [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Business, Innovation and Skills]]\n|term_start   = 20 May 2015\n|term_end     = 30 September 2015\n|predecessor  = Position established\n|successor    = [[Hannah Bardell]]\n|office1      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Edinburgh West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh West]]\n|term_start1  = 8 May 2015\n|term_end1    = 3 May 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Mike Crockart]]\n|successor1   = [[Christine Jardine]]\n|birth_name   = Michelle Rhonda Perks \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1965|3|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bearsden]], Scotland, UK\n|party        = [[Scottish National Party]]<br />{{small|(1981\u20132015, 2018\u2013)}}<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2015\u201317)}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland|Royal Scottish Academy of<br />Music and Drama]]\n}}\n'''Michelle Rhonda Thomson''' (born 11 March 1965) is a Scottish businesswoman and former [[politician]]. She is the co-founder of Momentous Change Ltd,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://momentouschangeltd.co.uk/|title=Momentous Change Ltd - Home|website=momentouschangeltd.co.uk}}</ref> a consultancy she set up with Professor [[Roger Mullin]] in 2017 to help organisations manage change. In 2018, Momentous Change published its first report, Brexit and Scottish Business.<ref>http://momentouschangeltd.co.uk/images/news/2018/FINAL_Brexit_and_Scottish_Business_report.pdf</ref>\n\nPrior to this, Thomson was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Edinburgh West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh West]] from May 2015 until May 2017. She served as the SNP Business, Innovation and Skills spokesperson in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] until her resignation of the party whip in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/2334493|title=List of Members returned to Parliament at the General Election 2015 Scotland|work=[[The Edinburgh Gazette]]|date=15 May 2015|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News\"/> She was also a member of the Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) Committee from 2015 to 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/business-energy-industrial-strategy/news-parliament-2015/2015-membership/|title=Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Committee membership at the end of Parliament 2015-17 - News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nSince stepping down from the House of Commons in 2017, she has been appointed as Ambassador for the All Party Parliamentary Group for Fair Business Banking.<ref>http://www.appgbanking.org.uk/about-us/</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nThomson graduated from the [[Royal Conservatoire of Scotland|Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] in 1985.\n\nThomson initially worked as a professional musician and then completed a post graduate diploma in [[Information technology]] (IT).<ref name=\"Who's Who 2017\">{{cite web|title=THOMSON, Michelle Rhonda|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U284018|website=Who's Who 2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=8 December 2016|date=November 2016}}</ref> She worked in Financial Services for [[Standard Life]] and the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] for over 23 years in a variety of senior roles delivering IT and business change. In 2009 she set up her own small business in property.<ref name=\"EN 9May2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/midlothian-elects-owen-thompson-as-council-leader-1-3194409 |title=Midlothian elects Owen Thompson as council leader |author=<!-- Staff writer/no by-line --> |work=[[Edinburgh Evening News]] |publisher=[[Johnston Press]] |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=11 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518094942/http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/midlothian-elects-owen-thompson-as-council-leader-1-3194409 |archive-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Indy\">{{cite news|last1=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/comment/the-city-should-not-dismiss-the-snp-as-a-single-issue-party-10193981.html|title=The City should not dismiss the SNP as a single issue party|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Momentous Change Ltd==\nThomson established Momentous Change Ltd in 2017 with co-founder Professor Roger Mullin. Momentous Change is a niche consultancy providing support to businesses through economic management and operational change. The firm self-funded research involving 236 senior Scottish business leaders across industry to establish their concerns over Brexit. The final report was published in February 2018. Its principal findings and recommendations included the need for a new skills strategy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16034112.uk-brexit-stance-is-against-the-interest-of-scottish-business/|title=UK Brexit stance is 'against' the interest of Scottish business|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref> and greater financial and practical support from government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/16038858.scottish-businesses-call-for-urgent-clarity-on-which-eu-powers-will-be-devolved-to-holyrood/|title=Scottish businesses call for 'urgent clarity' on which EU powers will be devolved to Holyrood|website=The National}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Thomson was a co-author of a Momentous Change Ltd report into the prospects for establishing a Scottish Stock Exchange.<ref>http://www.momentouschangeltd.co.uk/images/news/2018/Final-Report---Stock-Exchange.pdf</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nThomson joined the Scottish National Party at the age of sixteen in 1981.<ref name=\"Indy\"/> She became prominent politically during the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum campaign]], with the \"Yes\" campaign. She was elected as the Member of Parliament for Edinburgh West in 2015 with a majority of 3,210 votes and a 39% share of the vote; with a swing of 25.8% from Liberal Democrat to SNP.\n\nAs part of her role on the BEIS committee, Thomson was one of the members of the joint committee inquiries into the collapse of [[British Home Stores|BHS]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/work-and-pensions-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/bhs-inquiry-16-17/|title=BHS inquiry|website=UK Parliament|access-date=5 December 2016}}</ref> into the working practices of Sports Direct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/09/mike-ashley-asked-to-explain-camera-mps-sports-direct-visit-warehouse|title=Mike Ashley asked to explain 'secret filming' of MPs' Sports Direct visit|first=Sean|last=Farrell|date=9 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/07/six-mps-surprise-visit-sports-direct-shirebrook-warehouse|title=Sports Direct accused of secretly recording MPs during warehouse visit|first=Simon|last=Goodley|date=7 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Sunday Post]]'' described her as one of the SNP MPs to watch in the new parliament.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sundaypost.com/news-views/politics/out-with-the-old-and-in-with-the-new-12-snp-mps-to-watch-1.873640 | title=Out with the old and in with the new \u2013 12 SNP MPs to watch | first=James | last=Millar |work=[[Sunday Post]]| date=9 May 2015 | accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/scottish-mps-in-westminster-the-full-list-of-the-snp-parliamentarians-10234893.html | title=Scottish MPs in Westminster: The full list of the SNP parliamentarians | work=[[The Independent]] | first=Ben | last=Tufft | date=8 May 2015 | accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> [[The National (Scotland)|''The National'']] described Thomson as \"a breath of fresh air\" in light of her broad-based life experience.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.scot/politics/meet-your-new-scottish-mps-34-michelle-thomson-edinburgh-west.4904|title=Meet your new Scottish MPs: #34 Michelle Thomson, Edinburgh West|work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]]|location=Scotland|date=7 July 2015|last=Hannan|first=Martin}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, in a [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] debate focused on UN International Day For The Elimination Of Violence Against Women, Thomson described the impact of having been raped at the age of fourteen years old, highlighting the conditions of silence and shame that prevent rape from being discussed or reported.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-38250541|title=Michelle Thomson MP recalls being raped at age of 14|publisher=BBC News|date=8 December 2016|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThomson was sitting as an independent MP when the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 snap general election]] was called on 18 April 2017. The SNP's national executive met four days later and ruled that they would not endorse her as an SNP candidate. She did not stand as an independent at that election, issuing a statement that noted, \"even in political parties the concept of natural justice must apply, as must the need for defined processes that are applied fairly, rigorously and transparently. I would advise the SNP to employ the services of an external body to help them develop a process as soon as possible.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/michelle-thomson-to-step-down-as-mp-after-snp-ruling-1-4426630 |title=Michelle Thomson to step down as MP after SNP ruling |first=Russell |last=Jackson |work=The Scotsman |date=22 April 2017 |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Property allegations===\nIn September 2015, Thomson was accused by an article in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' of having built her buy-to-let property portfolio by buying homes for below-market prices.<ref>{{cite news |last=Macaskill |first=Mark |last2=Ungoed-Thomas |first2=Jon |date=20 September 2015 |title=SNP MP snaps up homes of struggling families |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/scotland/article1609551.ece |newspaper=[[The Times]]|access-date=21 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn late-September 2015, [[Police Scotland]] announced it had launched an inquiry into \"alleged irregularities\" related to the property transactions which had seen her solicitor struck off.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sanderson |first=Daniel |date=29 September 2015 |title=Police launch inquiry into property deals involving SNP MP |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13791520.Police_launch_into_inquiry_into_property_deals_involving_SNP_MP/ |newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |access-date=29 September 2015 }}</ref> The same day the SNP issued a statement on behalf of Thomson, announcing that she had decided to withdraw herself from the party whip whilst the investigation was ongoing. In resigning the whip, Thomson also lost her SNP membership and her role as the SNP's Business, Innovation and Skills spokesperson at Westminster.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |date=29 September 2015 |title=Probe over property deals on behalf of Michelle Thomson MP |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-34395392 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=29 September 2015 }}</ref> Thomson subsequently claimed she had been forced to resign the whip.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/ex-snp-mp-michelle-thomson-urges-nicola-sturgeon-to-apologise-to-her-after-being-cleared-in-mortgage-fraud-probe/|title=Ex-SNP MP Michelle Thomson urges Nicola Sturgeon to apologise to her after being cleared in mortgage fraud probe|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15456354.michelle-thomson-breaks-her-silence-my-two-years-of-hell/|title=Michelle Thomson breaks her silence: 'My two years of hell'|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-40842247|title=Scotland's papers: 'My two years of hell'|date=6 August 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nEight months after the story broke, Thomson issued a press statement noting that there had been no contact with her from [[Police Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14522314.suspended-snp-mp-reveals-lack-of-police-contact-amid-property-firm-investigation/|title=Suspended SNP MP reveals lack of police contact amid property firm investigation|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the investigation was dropped.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40788469|title=Michelle Thomson: Fraud case against former SNP MP dropped|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> Former Scottish Government Minister Kenny MacAskill said the SNP had lessons to learn over their handling of her case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/kenny-macaskill-lessons-to-be-learned-from-michelle-thomson-case-1-4526930|title=Kenny MacAskill: Lessons to be learned from Michelle Thomson case|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref> Former First Minister Alex Salmond was also quoted as saying how badly Thomson had been treated by the media and the SNP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40910096|title=Salmond criticises SNP over Thomson|date=12 August 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nShe rejoined the SNP in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/former-mp-michelle-thomson-has-rejoined-the-snp-1-4857567|title=Former MP Michelle Thomson has rejoined the SNP|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\"Why Banks Must Change\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://internationalbanker.com/banking/why-banks-must-change/|title=Why Banks Must Change|date=5 September 2018|website=International Banker}}</ref> International Banker, 5 September 2018. Retrieved 7 September 2018. [https://internationalbanker.com/banking/why-banks-must-change/ Why Banks Must Change]\n\n\"A Stock Exchange for Scotland: Early background research\", Momentous Change Ltd, November 2018.\n\n\"The Illusion Of Stability Gives Way To The Reality Of Change In Capital Markets - Introducing Scotland's New Stock Exchange\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://internationalbanker.com/brokerage/the-illusion-of-stability-gives-way-to-the-reality-of-change-in-capital-markets-introducing-scotlands-new-stock-exchange/|title=The Illusion Of Stability Gives Way To The Reality Of Change In Capital Markets - Introducing Scotland's New Stock |date=11 June 2019|website=International Banker}}</ref> International Banker, 11 June 2019. Retrieved 30 July 2019. [https://internationalbanker.com/brokerage/the-illusion-of-stability-gives-way-to-the-reality-of-change-in-capital-markets-introducing-scotlands-new-stock-exchange/ The Illusion of Stability Gives Way to the Reality of Change in Capital Markets: Introducing Scotland\u2019s New Stock Exchange]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150515075813/http://www.snp.org/people/michelle-thomson Profile] on [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] website\n* {{twitter | michellethomson | Michelle Thomson }}\n{{UK MP links\n| parliament   = michelle-thomson/4422\n| hansard      = \n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Michelle_Thomson&mpc=Edinburgh_West&house=commons\n| theywork     = 25352/michelle_thomson/edinburgh_west\n| record       = \n| bbc          = 137579.stm\n| journalisted =\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Crockart]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Edinburgh West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh West]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Christine Jardine]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Former SNP MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomson, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Edinburgh constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Bearsden]]\n[[Category:Rape in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Royal Bank of Scotland people]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n", "name_user": "Notananwar", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications:added publication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelle_Thomson"}
{"title_page": "Ranked-choice voting in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|Electoral system used in some cities in the United States}}\nRanked-choice voting (RCV), also known as [[instant-runoff voting]] (IRV), is used for state primary, congressional, and presidential (beginning in [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]]) elections in [[Maine]] and for local elections in more than 20 US cities including [[San Francisco, California]]; [[Oakland, California]]; [[Berkeley, California]]; [[San Leandro, California]]; [[Takoma Park, Maryland]]; [[St. Paul, Minnesota]]; [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]; [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]; [[Portland, Maine]]; [[Las Cruces, New Mexico]]; and [[St. Louis Park, Minnesota]].<ref name=where>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairvote.org/where_is_ranked_choice_voting_used|title=Where is Ranked Choice Voting Used?|publisher=FairVote|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>  [[New York City]] is by far the largest voting population in the US that has opted for RCV, pending implementation in 2021.<ref name=\"RCV officially adopted in NYC\">{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/New_York_City_Ballot_Question_1,_Elections_Charter_Amendment:_Ranked-Choice_Voting,_Vacancies,_and_City_Council_Redistricting_Timeline_(November_2019)|title=New York City Ballot Question 1, Elections Charter Amendment: Ranked-Choice Voting, Vacancies, and City Council Redistricting Timeline (November 2019)|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> RCV is commonly used for student leadership and other non-governmental elections.<ref name=where/> It has been proposed for presidential elections and will be used in four states in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref name=\"The Case for Using Ranked Choice Voting in the 2020 Democratic Presidential Primaries\">{{Cite journal |url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/21814/ranked-choice-voting-2020-democratic-presidential-primary-bernie-sanders |title=The Case for Using Ranked Choice Voting in the 2020 Democratic Presidential Primaries |last=Eichen |first=Adam |date=2019-04-01 |journal=In These Times |access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> \n\nBetween 1912 and 1930, limited forms of RCV (typically with only two rankings<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/effectivevoting00hoaggoog|title=Effective Voting: An Article on Preferential Voting and Proportional Representation|last=Hoag|first=Clarence Gilbert|date=1914|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|language=en}}</ref>) were implemented and subsequently repealed in [[Florida]], [[Indiana]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], and [[Wisconsin]]. In the 1970s, it was implemented and repealed in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://migreens.org/hvgreens/aa-irv01.htm|title=Instant Runoff Voting: History in Ann Arbor, Michigan|last=Walter|first=Benjamin|date=2001-08-26|work=Green Party of Michigan|access-date=2018-01-02|archive-url=https://archive.today/20080917220033/http://migreens.org/hvgreens/aa-irv01.htm|archive-date=September 17, 2008|url-status = dead}}</ref>  More recently, it was adopted and repealed in [[Pierce County, Washington]] (2006\u20132009);<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.sos.wa.gov/FromOurCorner/index.php/2009/11/pierce-voters-nix-ranked-choice-voting/|title=Pierce voters nix 'ranked-choice voting' \u2013 From Our Corner|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2009|website=blogs.sos.wa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref> [[Burlington, Vermont]] (2005\u20132010);<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://vprarchive.vpr.net/vpr-news/burlington-voters-repeal-instant-runoff-voting/|title=Burlington Voters Repeal Instant Runoff Voting|last=McCrea|first=Lynne|date=2010-03-03|website=Vermont Public Radio|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-02}}</ref> [[Aspen, Colorado]] (2007-2010);<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.aspendailynews.com/city-voters-repeal-irv/article_5d3a9245-bfc1-55db-947b-fefdb87031ea.html|title=City voters repeal IRV|last=Wackerle|first=Curtis|date=November 3, 2010|work=Aspen Daily News|access-date=2018-01-02|language=en}}</ref> and in North Carolina, which allowed its use in certain elections between 2006 and 2013.\n\nIn 2016, voters in Maine approved an [[Initiatives and referendums in the United States|initiative]] to become the first state to use RCV statewide in elections for governor, state legislature, U.S. Senate, and U.S. House.<ref name=\"boston.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/politics/2016/11/10/maine-became-the-first-state-in-the-country-to-pass-ranked-choice-voting|title=Maine became the first state in the country Tuesday to pass ranked choice voting|date=November 10, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref> Despite a ruling by the [[Maine Supreme Judicial Court|state supreme court]] that RCV was inconsistent with the requirements of the [[Maine Constitution]] for the elections of [[Governor of Maine|governor]] and state legislature, and despite subsequent efforts by the [[Maine state legislature|state legislature]] to delay implementation of RCV, a [[popular referendum|veto referendum]] campaign kept the RCV law in place, with the state supreme court ruling that RCV would be introduced for the primary on June 12, 2018. In that election, Maine voters re-affirmed implementation of RCV by popular referendum while using RCV for the first time in primaries for the offices of governor, U.S. House, and state legislator.<ref name=Maine2018 /> The November [[United States House of Representatives elections in Maine, 2018#Results 6|general election]] for [[Maine's 2nd congressional district]] saw the loss of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Bruce Poliquin]] in the second round to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[Jared Golden]].<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/15/668296045/ranked-choice-voting-delivers-another-victory-to-house-democrats |title=Ranked-Choice Voting Delivers Democrats A House Seat |date=November 15, 2018 |publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Use at presidential level==\n===Maine, starting 2020===\nOn August 26, 2019, the Maine legislature passed a bill adopting RCV for both presidential primaries and general election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2019/08/26/maine-senate-passes-ranked-choice-voting-for-march-presidential-primaries/|title=Maine Senate passes ranked-choice voting for March presidential primaries|last=Miller|first=Kevin|date=August 26, 2019|work=[[Portland Press Herald]]|access-date=August 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wgme.com/news/local/maine-might-switch-to-a-ranked-choice-presidential-election-heres-how-it-would-look|title=Maine might switch to a ranked-choice presidential election. Here's how it would look.|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=August 28, 2019|work=[[CBS]] 13|access-date=August 28, 2019}}</ref> On September 6, 2019, Governor [[Janet Mills]] allowed the bill to become law without her signature, which delayed it from taking effect until after the [[2020 Maine Democratic primary|2020 Democratic primary]] in March but puts Maine on track to be the first state to use RCV for a presidential general election. The law continues the use of the [[United States Electoral College#Congressional district method|congressional district method]] for the allocation of electors, as [[Maine]] and [[Nebraska]] have used in recent elections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/09/06/politics/maine-will-use-ranked-choice-voting-in-next-years-presidential-election-but-not-the-2020-primaries/|title=Maine will use ranked-choice voting in next year's presidential election \u2014 but not the 2020 primaries|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=September 6, 2019|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> The change could potentially delay projection of the winner(s) of Maine's electoral votes for days after election day,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Berman |first1=Russell |title=A Step Toward Blowing Up the Presidential-Voting System |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/09/ranked-choice-voting-2020/598303/ |website=The Atlantic |accessdate=14 January 2020|date=2019-09-20 }}</ref> and will also complicate interpretation of the national [[direct election|popular vote]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muller |first1=Derek |title=Maine, ranked choice voting, and the National Popular Vote Compact |url=https://excessofdemocracy.com/blog/2019/7/maine-ranked-choice-voting-and-the-national-popular-vote-compact |website=Excess of Democracy |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Democratic presidential primaries, 2020 ===\nSix states planned to use RCV in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]]: Alaska, Hawaii, Kansas, and Wyoming for all voters; Iowa and Nevada for absentee voters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/21959/ranked-choice-voting-2020-democratic-primary-maine-kansas|title=Ranked Choice Voting Is On a Roll: 6 States Have Opted In for the 2020 Democratic Primary|last=Daley|first=David|date=2019-07-09|work=In These Times|access-date=2019-08-22|language=en-US|issn=0160-5992}}</ref> Rather than eliminating candidates until a single winner is chosen, voters' choices would be reallocated until all remaining candidates have at least 15%, the threshold to receive delegates to the convention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairvote.org/how_ranked_choice_voting_will_affect_democratic_presidential_primary|title=How ranked choice voting will affect Democratic presidential primary|last=FairVote.org|website=FairVote|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\nWhile it\u2019s legal in Maine Maine chose not to use RCV to avoid losing delegates. <ref>{{cite web |title=Maine will use ranked-choice voting in next year\u2019s presidential election \u2014 but not the 2020 primaries |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/09/06/politics/maine-will-use-ranked-choice-voting-in-next-years-presidential-election-but-not-the-2020-primaries/ |website=Bangor Daily News |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Use at state and federal levels==\n===Maine, 2018\u2013present===\n[[Maine Question 5, 2016]] asked Maine voters whether to implement RCV for primary and general elections for governor, U.S. Senate, U.S. House and state legislature, starting in 2018. It was approved by 52% to 48%, making Maine the first state to use RCV for all such elections.<ref name=\"boston.com\"/> However, on May 23, 2017, the [[Maine Supreme Judicial Court]] issued an advisory opinion stating that the [[Constitution of Maine|state constitution]] specified that for general elections for governor and the state legislature only a plurality was required to win, which is not consistent with the use of RCV and its multi-round vote transfers to ensure majority support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/3728801-Maine-Supreme-Judicial-Court-ruling-on-Ranked.html |title=Opinion of the Justices of the Supreme Judicial Court |date=23 May 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, the legislature debated legislation to propose a constitutional amendment, to repeal the measure entirely, and to keep RCV in place for elections for U.S. Senate, U.S. House and primaries. All bills failed to pass in the regularly scheduled legislative session, but the legislature voted in October 2017 to delay implementation until 2021, by which time either a constitutional amendment must be adopted or the entire law would be considered repealed.<ref name=\"Portland Press Herald\">{{cite news|last1=Thistle|first1=Scott|title=Legislature delays and potentially repeals ranked-choice voting|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2017/10/23/in-special-session-legislature-cant-break-impasse-on-ranked-choice-voting/|accessdate=28 October 2017|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|date=October 24, 2017}}</ref> Maine voters then collected enough signatures to force a veto referendum of the parts of the new law that blocked use of RCV for primary and congressional elections. In April 2018, the Maine Supreme Judicial Court ruled against a legal challenge seeking to prevent RCV from being used in state primaries and elections for federal office starting in June 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2018/04/17/politics/maines-top-court-clears-way-for-ranked-choice-voting-in-june/|title=Maine's top court clears way for ranked-choice voting in June|work=Bangor Daily News|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en-US}}</ref> The people's veto, [[Maine Question 1, June 2018|Question 1]], passed in the June 12, 2018 election, which was also the first election that used RCV for state and federal offices, including Republican and Democratic primaries for governor, the Democratic primary for the 2nd Congressional District, and the Republican primary for House District 75.<ref name=Maine2018>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/06/12/ranked-choice-voting-takes-lead-in-early-balloting/ |title=Mainers vote to keep ranked-choice voting, with supporters holding commanding lead |newspaper=Portland Press Herald |first=Eric |last=Russell |date=June 12, 2018 |accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMaine removed rank choice voting from primaries in 2020 [[Super Tuesday]] per the request of the [[Democratic National Committee]] (DNC) and the [[Republican National Committee]] (RNC) to avoid having to lose delegates  due to the rules and hopes the DNC and RNC will allow the use in 2024 without losing delegates However it\u2019s still allowed and will be used in the presidential election <ref>{{cite web |title=Maine will use ranked-choice voting in next year\u2019s presidential election \u2014 but not the 2020 primaries |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/09/06/politics/maine-will-use-ranked-choice-voting-in-next-years-presidential-election-but-not-the-2020-primaries/ |website=Bangor Daily News |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n====2018 Congressional election====\nIn the November 2018 general election, though [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Bruce Poliquin]] led in the first round of votes of the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Maine, 2018#Results 6|2nd Congressional District election]] by 2,171 votes, the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[Jared Golden]] won with a majority of 3,509 votes in the final round count after votes for [[independent (politician)|independent]] candidates Tiffany Bond and Will Hoar were transferred to the totals of the top two candidates.<ref name=\":9\" /> As a result, Poliquin became the first incumbent to lose the [[Maine's 2nd congressional district|2nd Congressional District]] since 1916.\n\n===North Carolina, 2006\u20132013===\nA 2006 law had established that RCV would be used when judicial vacancies were created between a primary election and sixty days before a general election.  In November 2010, [[North Carolina]] had three RCV elections for local-level [[North Carolina Superior Court|superior court]] judges, each with three candidates, and [[North Carolina judicial elections, 2010#Court of Appeals (Wynn seat)|a statewide RCV election]] for a [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]] seat (with 13 candidates). The Court of Appeals race is believed to be the first time RCV has been used in any statewide general election in the United States.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe statewide RCV law was repealed by the General Assembly in 2013 as part of a sweeping [[Voter ID laws in the United States|voter ID bill]], meaning that special judicial elections with more than two candidates would once again be decided by a simple plurality.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/election-changes-coming-in-2014-2016/12750290/|title=Q&A: Changes to NC election laws|last=Binker|first=Mark|date=2013-08-12|website=WRAL.com|accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=http://ncleg.net/Sessions/2013/Bills/House/PDF/H589v9.pdf|title=GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA : SESSION 2013 : SESSION LAW 2013-381 : HOUSE BILL 589|website=Ncleg.net|accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Party primaries, caucuses, and conventions===\n====Florida, Indiana, Maryland, Minnesota, and Wisconsin, 1912\u20131930====\nIn the United States, RCV election laws were first adopted in 1912. Five states ([[Florida]], [[Indiana]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], and [[Wisconsin]]) used versions of RCV for party [[primary election|primaries]], typically with each voter having two rankings and candidates needing to finish in the top two to advance to the instant runoff (also known as [[Supplementary vote|supplementary voting]]). By 1930 each jurisdiction had replaced RCV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairvote.org/irv/vt_lite/history.htm|title=The History of Instant Runoff Voting|last=|first=|date=|website=FairVote.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028050940/http://www.fairvote.org/irv/vt_lite/history.htm|archivedate=October 28, 2009|url-status = dead|accessdate=November 9, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairvotemn.org/sites/fairvotemn.org/files/Municipal%20Voting%20System%20Reform%20article.pdf|title=Municipal Voting System Reform: Overcoming the Legal Obstacles|last=Solg\u00e5rd|first=Tony Anderson|author2=Paul Landskroener|website=Fairvotemn.org|accessdate=2016-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002231/http://fairvotemn.org/sites/fairvotemn.org/files/Municipal%20Voting%20System%20Reform%20article.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CHLvGawRmEwC&pg|title=Democracy in Divided Societies: Electoral Engineering for Conflict Management|last=Reilly|first=Ben|date=2001-09-13|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521797306|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Republican Party of Utah====\nAfter voting to authorize its use, the Republican Party of [[Utah]] used RCV in 2002, 2003 and 2004 at its statewide convention,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fairvote.org/editorials/herald.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 13, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724222543/http://fairvote.org/editorials/herald.htm |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}</ref> including in a contested race to nominate a governor in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fairvote.org/irv/utahresults.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 13, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205061342/http://www.fairvote.org/irv/utahresults.htm |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref> In 2005, Republicans used repeated balloting for its statewide convention and has done so in subsequent years. Some county Republican parties like Cache County continue to use instant runoff voting at their conventions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cachegop.com/web/bylaws.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 13, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106034733/http://www.cachegop.com/web/bylaws.pdf |archivedate=January 6, 2009 }}</ref> and IRV was used by Republicans to fill several state legislative vacancies in 2009-2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairvote.org/e-newsletter-january-28-201#rtv |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 12, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726045132/http://www.fairvote.org/e-newsletter-january-28-201 |archivedate=July 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====Democratic Party of Virginia====\nIn 2014, the Democratic Party of [[Arlington, Virginia]] used RCV in two \"[[firehouse primary|firehouse primaries]]\" for countywide office that each drew several thousand voters, and it joined with the Democratic Party of Fairfax county that year to use RCV in a seven-candidate primary election for a special election for the House of Delegates.<ref>{{cite web|first= Grace |last=Ramsey |url=http://www.fairvote.org/research-and-analysis/blog/party-in-major-virginia-county-uses-instant-runoff-voting-and-voters-like-it/ |title=Party in Major Virginia County Uses Instant Runoff Voting \u2013 and Voters Like It |work=FairVote.org  |date=2014-12-05 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Arlington Democrats also used the system in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|first= Ethan |last=Fitzgerald  |url=http://www.fairvote.org/over_1_700_virginia_democrats_participate_in_ranked_choice_voting_election |title= Over 1,700 Virginia Democrats Participate in Ranked Choice Voting Election|work=FairVote.org  |date=2016-05-24 |accessdate=2016-11-13}}</ref>\n\nRCV was also used in 2014 by leaders of the Henrico County Democrats in a three-candidate special election nomination contest for the House of Delegates in December 2014 <ref>{{cite web|last=Schmidt |first=Markus |url=http://www.roanoke.com/news/politics/kevin-sullivan-defends-firehouse-primary-for-morrissey-s-seat/article_f3506d23-c62d-5c91-986a-8ff16b99996d.html |title=Kevin Sullivan defends firehouse primary for Morrissey's seat - Roanoke Times: Politics |website=Roanoke.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, the Democratic Party of [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], held its first open caucus to select its nominees for city council and sheriff, using RCV. Voter turnout was close to 1,600 voters. One of two city council incumbents was renominated and another was defeated by a challenger without the need for an instant runoff. Three candidates ran in the sheriff's race. No candidate won an initial majority. In the instant runoff, James E. Brown III defeated Mike Baird.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fairvote.org/charlottesville-va-democrats-use-irv-to-nominate-candidates-in-high-turnout-open-caucus |title=Charlottesville (VA) Democrats use IRV to nominate candidates in high turnout open caucus |publisher=FairVote |date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, the Party again used to nominate candidates. Voter turnout rose to 2,582 in the city council race for three nominations. Two candidates were nominated with a majority of the first round vote. The final nomination was determined by RCV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cvillepedia.org/mediawiki/images/2011_Democratic_Primary_City_Council_Votes.pdf |title=Vote Count Summary for City Council |website=Cvillepedia.org |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n====Independence Party of Minnesota (2004 Presidential poll)====\nIn part to increase awareness of the voting method and to demonstrate it in a real-world situation, the [[Independence Party of Minnesota]] tested RCV by using it in a [[straw poll]] during the 2004 [[Minnesota]] [[caucus]]es.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnip.org/caucusresults.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 29, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206193035/http://mnip.org/caucusresults.shtml |archivedate=February 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe poll allowed a [[none of the above]] option which could not be eliminated. Their rules eliminated one weakest candidate at a time, or all candidates in a tie at the bottom. They continued the elimination until only one candidate remained to confirm that this candidate had more support than none of the above.\n\nThis summary table shows the first round, and final five rounds, excluding five rounds during which 18 weak candidates were eliminated.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidate/Round ||1||\u2026||7||8||9||10||11\n|-\n![[John Edwards]]<br />(Democrat)\n|94<br />(20.75%)||&nbsp;||106<br />(23.40%)||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''131<br />(28.92%)'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''166<br />(36.64%)'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''210<br />(46.36%)'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''335<br />(73.95%)'''</span>\n|-\n![[John F. Kerry]]<br />(Democrat) \n|<span style=\"color:red;\">'''100<br />(22.08%)'''</span>||&nbsp;||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''110<br />(24.28%)'''</span>||117<br />(25.83%)||132<br />(29.14%)||149<br />(32.89%)||0<br />(0.00%)\n|-\n![[George W. Bush]]<br />(Republican)\n|77<br />(17.0