 web|url=http://www.acgov.org/rov_app/current_election/customindex.jsp |title=Election Results - Alameda County Registrar of Voters |website=Acgov.org |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Berkeley used IRV for electing its mayor and four city council seats in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lance |last=Knobel |url=http://www.berkeleyside.com/2012/04/26/berkeleys-mayor-bates-announces-his-re-election-bid/ |title=Berkeley's Mayor Bates announces his re-election bid |publisher=Berkeleyside |date=2012-04-26 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> The city continues to use RCV, including in city elections in November 2014 and November 2016.<ref name=\"fairvote1\">[https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/fairvote/pages/426/attachments/original/1449179101/CivilityBriefForApsa2015_Updated.pdf \"Ranked Choice Voting in Practice: Candidate Civility in Ranked Choice Elections\"], FairVote, 2015.</ref>\n\n====Oakland====\nThe city of [[Oakland, California]], passed (69%) a measure in November 2006 to adopt RCV for 18 city offices.<ref>[http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/11/08/BAG9LM8J2U4.DTL Offbeat and practical issues taken up around Bay Area], Heather Knight, [[San Francisco Chronicle]], Nov. 8, 2006.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidebayarea.com/oaklandtribune/localnews/ci_14132699 |title=Instant-runoff voting a go for Oakland |publisher=Inside Bay Area |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In November 2010, Oakland used RCV to elect its mayor, three city council races and four other local offices, with elections for mayor and council district four requiring multiple rounds of counting.<ref name=\"acgov.org\"/> It used RCV in the city's remaining elected offices in 2012. IRV was again used in 2014 and 2016, including in the 2014 mayoral election in which incumbent [[Jean Quan]] was defeated by [[Libby Schaaf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Oakland,_California_municipal_elections,_2014 |title=Oakland, California municipal elections, 2014 |publisher=Ballotpedia |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=====2010 mayoral election=====\nOakland's 2010 mayoral election was an open-seat election in which no candidate earned more than 34% of votes in the first round. In the tally, candidates were eliminated sequentially, with three candidates far ahead in first choices. After the count of first choices, Don Perata was in first place, Jean Quan in second place, and Rebecca Kaplan in third place. They remained in that order of votes after all other candidates were eliminated and their votes re-allocated. When Kaplan was then eliminated, Quan picked up 18,864 votes from Kaplan backers while Perata was the next choice of only 6,407 Kaplan backers. As a result, Quan won a final round majority when matched against Perata, which means she was ranked ahead of Perata on a majority of ballots in which one of them received a ranking.(11% of voters did not rank either of them, making their votes exhausted by the time of the final round.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acgov.org/rov/rcv/results/rcvresults_2984.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 11, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115182601/http://www.acgov.org/rov/rcv/results/rcvresults_2984.htm |archivedate=November 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Candidate\n!colspan=3|Round 1\n!rowspan=2|\u2026\n!colspan=3|Round 9\n!colspan=2|Round 10\n|-\n!Votes||%<sup>(*)</sup>||Transfer||Votes||%<sup>(*)</sup>||Transfer||Votes||%<sup>(*)</sup>\n|-\n|[[Don Perata]]||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''40,342'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''33.73%'''</span>||+32||||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''45,465'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''40.16%'''</span>||+6,407||51,872||49.04%\n|-\n|'''[[Jean Quan]]'''||29,266||24.47%||+33||||35,033||30.94%||+18,864||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''53,897'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''50.96%'''</span>\n|-\n|[[Rebecca Kaplan]]||25,813||21.58%||+18||||32,719||28.90%||-32,719||||\n|-\n|Joe Tuman||14,347||12.00%||+10||||||||||||\n|-\n|Marcie Hodge||2,994||2.50%||+5||||||||||||\n|-\n|Terence Candell||2,315||1.94%||+1||||||||||||\n|-\n|Don MacLeay||1,630||1.36%||+6||||||||||||\n|-\n|Greg Harland||966||0.81%||+2||||||||||||\n|-\n|Larry Lionel ''LL'' Young Jr.||933||0.78%||+6||||||||||||\n|-\n|Arnold Fields||733||0.61%||+5||||||||||||\n|-\n|Write-In||268||0.22%||-268||||||||||||\n|-\n|Continuing Ballots||119,607||100.00%||||||113,217||100.00%||||105,769||100.00%\n|-\n|Exhausted Ballots||0||||+149||||6,284||||+7,383||13,667|||\n|-\n|Overvotes||355||||+1||||461||||+65||526|||\n|-\n|Undervotes||2,306||||||||2,306||||||2,306|||\n|-\n|Total Ballots||122,268||||||||122,268||||||122,268|||\n|}\n\n=====2012 elections=====\nOakland used RCV for several elections in 2012, including a citywide election for city attorney and for several seats on the city council and school board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zennie62blog.com/2012/06/07/oakland-city-council-will-change-oaklanders-get-to-decide-how-dan-cohen-48125/ |title=Oakland City Council Will Change; Oaklanders Get To Decide How \u2013 Dan Cohen |website=Zennie62blog.com |date=2012-06-07 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Several races were decided after multiple rounds, including the District 3 city council race where the winner trailed in first choices.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mollie |last=Hailey  |url=http://www.fairvote.org/fairvote-s-first-take-on-rcv-elections-in-four-bay-area-cities |title=FairVote's First Take on RCV Elections in Four Bay Area Cities |work=FairVote.org  |date=2012-11-12 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Of the 18 Oakland offices elected by RCV in 2010 and 2012, sixteen of the RCV winners received more votes than the previous winner had won before adoption in the last non-RCV election <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fairvote.org/assets/Oakland-RCV-Analysis-2012.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-01-06 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20130106162800/http://www.fairvote.org/assets/Oakland-RCV-Analysis-2012.pdf |archive-date=2013-01-06 |url-status = bot: unknown}}</ref>\n\n====San Francisco====\n[[San Francisco]] has used RCV for its Board of Supervisors and most citywide offices nearly every November since 2004. In March 2002, an initiative backed by a broad coalition of civic organizations<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sfrcv.org/articles/fulfillthewill.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2004-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041027065038/http://www.sfrcv.org/articles/fulfillthewill.htm |archive-date=2004-10-27 |url-status = bot: unknown}}</ref> won 55% of the vote to adopt ranked-choice voting. A unanimous panel of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] upheld San Francisco's RCV law as constitutional.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?q=dudum+v+arntz&hl=en&as_sdt=2003&case=438379963242494061&scilh=0 |title=Google Scholar |website=Scholar.google.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nRCV was first used in October 2004 for YouthVOTE, an election held throughout San Francisco's public schools which elected the San Francisco school board's student delegate;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/HL0411/S00013.htm |title=And It's 1, 2, 3: That's What We're Fighting For &#124; Scoop News |website=Scoop.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> after that, it was used in the November 2004 supervisoral races and every November since that time for at least one election in the city. RCV has played a decisive role in at least one city election in 2004, 2005, 2006, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfrcv.com |title=SFRCV |publisher=Sfrcv.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Exit polls<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pri.sfsu.edu/reports/SFSU-PRI_RCV_final_report_July_17_2006.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 28, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070728043742/http://pri.sfsu.edu/reports/SFSU-PRI_RCV_final_report_July_17_2006.pdf |archivedate=July 28, 2007 }}</ref> by San Francisco State University have shown support for the new system from all groupings of voters.\n\nThe San Francisco Department of Elections prefers the term ranked-choice voting rather than instant-runoff voting because \"the word 'instant' might create an expectation that final results will be available ''immediately'' after the polls close on election night.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairvote.org/media/irv/sanfrancisco/RCVCandidateGuide04.pdf|title=Ranked-Choice Voting: A Guide for Candidates|last=Arntz|first=John|date=February 2, 2005|website=|publisher=Department of Elections: City and County of San Francisco|via=[[FairVote]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202040611/http://fairvote.org/media/irv/sanfrancisco/RCVCandidateGuide04.pdf|archivedate=December 2, 2008|url-status = dead|accessdate=August 25, 2009}}</ref> The department used to release first-choice totals immediately but wait until more absentee ballots arrived before running subsequent rounds of counting. That practice has since changed.\n\nSan Francisco continues to hold RCV elections as of 2017, several of which have gone to multiple rounds of counting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfbetterelections.com/reports.html |title=Reports - Better Elections in San Francisco |website=Sfbetterelections.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In 2010, for example, two candidates won who were not the leaders in first-choice rankings. In 2011, all three citywide elections up for election- mayor, sheriff and district attorney\u2014 were decided in RCV tallies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairvote.org/san-francisco-voters-effectively-used-ranked-choice-voting |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 11, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306182324/http://www.fairvote.org/san-francisco-voters-effectively-used-ranked-choice-voting |archivedate=March 6, 2012 }}</ref> In the wake of the November 2012 elections, sixteen of eighteen offices elected by RCV were held by people of color.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mollie |last=Hailey |url=http://www.fairvote.org/fairvote-s-first-take-on-rcv-elections-in-four-bay-area-cities/ |title=FairVote's First Take on RCV Elections in Four Bay Area Cities |work=FairVote.org |date=2012-11-12 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nElection results for 2004, 2005, and 2006 are provided in greater detail below.\n\n=====2004 results=====\nThere were four elections that used multiple rounds of counting after there was no majority winner in the first round: Districts 1,5,7, and 11.\n* District 1: There were 7 candidates, reduced to 2 candidates in 4 rounds. The winner won 54% of the final round count, which amounted to 48.67% of the total first-round votes, with 9.89% of the ballots exhausted by the final round.\n* District 5: There were 22 candidates, reduced to 3 in 19 rounds, when the winner had a majority of active ballots. The winner finished with 50.6% of the final round vote against two runners up, which amounted to 37.63% of the first-round vote with 25.63% of the ballots exhausted.\n* District 7: There were 13 candidates, reduced to 2 in 11 rounds. The winner finished with 57% of the votes cast for the two active candidates in the final round. Of first round votes, this amounted to 43.72% of the first-round vote, with 23.12% exhausted ballots.\n* District 11: There were 8 candidates, reduced to 2 in 6 rounds. The winner finished with 58% of the final round vote, which amounted to 46.08% of the total first-round vote, with 21.01% of the ballots exhausted.\n\nThe District 5 results are included below as the largest election from 2004 and the one with the most rounds of counting. The elimination table shows the candidates reordered by their elimination. The elimination process was stable for the highest 5 candidates, holding their same plurality ranking each round despite the 19 rounds of elimination and transfer votes.\n\nThe RCV elimination process was halted when candidate Mirkarimi reached more than 50% of the active ballots, but only 37.6% of the total first-round ballots. This stopping point is pragmatic for picking a winner, but fails to show how many votes the winner had compared to only the strongest runner up candidate.\n\n=====2005 results=====\nThere was one election requiring multiple rounds of counting, with 4 candidates and finding a 55% majority winner in two rounds.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ November 8, 2005: RCV Assessor-Recorder<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgov.org/site/elections_page.asp?id%3D61454 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 3, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205031721/http://www.sfgov.org/site/elections_page.asp?id=61454 |archivedate=February 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n!Candidate||colspan=2|Pass 1||colspan=2|Pass 2\n|-\n|PHIL TING||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''94062'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''47.21%'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''110053'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''55.24%'''</span>\n|-\n|GERARDO SANDOVAL||71850||36.06%||79261||39.78%\n|-\n|RONALD CHUN||33294||16.71%||||\n|-\n|ANTHONY FABER||18||0.01%||||\n|-\n!Eligible Ballots||199224||100%||189314||95.03%\n|-\n!Exhausted Ballots<br />(-26146 no marks)||0||0.00%||9910||4.97%\n|-\n!Total Ballots|| 199224||||199224||\n|}\n\n=====2006 results=====\nThere were [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors elections, 2006|two elections]] that required multiple rounds of counting, districts 4 and 6:\n* District 4: There were 6 candidates which were reduced to 2 in 4 rounds. The winner ended with 52.5% of the final round vote for active candidates, which amounted to 42.33% of the first-round vote, with 19.38% exhausted ballots.\n* District 6: There were 8 candidates and was stopped on the second round with 4 candidates remaining. The winner had 49.99% of the total first-round votes, with 48.37% divided among the 3 runners up, and 1.64% exhausted ballots.\n\nThe detailed runoff results for district 4 are:\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ San Francisco 2006 MEMBER, BOARD OF SUPERVISORS DIST. 4<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgov.org/site/elections_index.asp?id%3D55671 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 4, 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091108025306/http://www.sfgov.org/site/elections_index.asp?id=55671 |archivedate=November 8, 2009 }}</ref>\n!Race and Candidate||colspan=2|Pass 1||colspan=2|Pass 2||colspan=2|Pass 3||colspan=2|Pass 4\n|-\n|[[Ed Jew|ED JEW]]||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''5184'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''26.16%'''</span>||5441||27.46%||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''6455'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''32.58%'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''8388'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''42.33%'''</span>\n|-\n|RON DUDUM||5134||25.91%||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''5521'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''27.86%'''</span>||6305||31.82%||7587||38.29%\n|-\n|JAYNRY MAK||4569||23.06%||5012||25.30%||5851||29.53%||||\n|-\n|DOUG CHAN||3236||16.33%||3414||17.23%||||||||\n|-\n|DAVID FERGUSON||1455||7.34%||||||||||||\n|-\n|HOUSTON ZHENG||234||1.18%||||||||||||\n|-\n|WRITE-IN||2||0.01%||||||||||||\n|-\n!Eligible Ballots<br />(-2171 no marks)||19814||100.00%||19388||97.85%||18611||93.93%||15975||80.62%\n|-\n!Exhausted Ballots||0||0.00%||426||2.15%||1203||6.07%||3839||19.38%\n|-\n!Total Ballots||19814||100%||19814||100%||19814||100%||19814||100%\n|}\n\n====San Leandro====\nIn November 2000, the voters of [[San Leandro, California]] approved a charter amendment by 63% to 37% requiring use of a two-round runoff or ranked-choice if no candidate won a majority of first round votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fairvote.org/irv/irvwins.htm |title=Center for Voting and Democracy |website=Archive.fairvote.org |date=2000-11-07 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In January 2010, the city council voted 5-2 to use RCV for its elections for mayor and three city council seats in November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Holmes |first=Tim |url=http://www.sanleandrobytes.com/archives/009400.html |title=City Council Approves Ranked Choice Voting - Election is Nov. 2, 2010 |publisher=San Leandro Bytes |date=2010-01-20 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> The mayor's race required multiple rounds of counting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairvote.org/san-leandro-facts |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 1, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324084245/http://www.fairvote.org/san-leandro-facts |archivedate=March 24, 2012 }}</ref>  Challenger [[Stephen H. Cassidy]] narrowly defeated incumbent Mayor Tony Santos in the final vote by a 50.57% to 49.43% margin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acvote.org/acvote-assets/pdf/elections/2010/11022010/results/rcv/san_leandro/mayor/november-2-2010-pass-report-san-leandro-mayor.pdf|title=San Leandro Mayor Pass Report|last=Alameda County Registrar of Voters|date=|website=|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2012, San Leandro held RCV elections for three city council seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sanleandro.patch.com/articles/san-leandro-political-season-officially-opens |title=San Leandro Political Season Officially Opens &#124; Patch |website=Sanleandro.patch.com |date=2012-07-16 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> One election was decided in first choices, and two with multiple rounds of counting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acgov.org/rov/rcv/results/index.htm |title=Ranked-Choice Voting - Registrar of Voters - Alameda County |website=Acgov.org |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In November 2014 and November 2016, San Leandro used RCV for electing six city council seats and the mayor.\n\nThe November 2018 elections used RCV for the mayor and three council seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanleandro.org/depts/cityhall/election/ranked_choice_voting.asp|title=Ranked Choice Voting|last=City of San Leandro|date=|website=|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==== Palm Desert ====\nTo settle a California Voting Rights Act challenge, [[Palm Desert, California]] will switch from an at-large election for its city council to RCV in 2020. One of its five members will be elected in a single-member district, while the other four will be elected in a multimember district, electing two members every two years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/local/palm-desert/2019/12/12/palm-desert-reaches-california-voting-rights-act-settlement/4410780002/|title=Palm Desert lawsuit settlement includes two-district elections; ranked-choice voting system possible for 2020|website=Desert Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\n===Colorado===\n====Aspen====\n[[Aspen, Colorado]] passed RCV in November 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20071107/NEWS/111070039 |title=Voters approve instant runoff voting |website=AspenTimes.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> for the mayoral race and for at-large council races with two winners. In March 2009, the Aspen council adopted a unique variation of RCV for the council races.<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Aspen council adopts instant runoff voting method\n |work         = AspenTimes.com\n |accessdate   = 2009-08-18\n |url          = http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20090310/NEWS/903099950/-1/rss03\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110908022300/http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20090310/NEWS/903099950/-1/rss03\n |archive-date = 2011-09-08\n |url-status = dead|df           = \n}}</ref> A [[Preferential block voting|block voting]] tally based on the first and second rank choices was used to determine first round support. Any candidate with initial majority support was elected. If there were not two first-round winners, there was a batch elimination of low-placing candidates to reduce the number of continuing candidates before the instant runoff. In the latter case, separate rounds of ranked-choice counting would be conducted for each council seat, with the winner of the first seat eliminated from the race for the second seat.\n\nAspen's first elections with RCV and the new city council system were on May 5, 2009. The number of voters was the highest in the history of Aspen elections.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Aspen voter turnout breaks record |work= AspenTimes.com\n| accessdate = 2009-08-18\n| url = http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20090506/NEWS/905069969/1077&ParentProfile=1058\n}}</ref> Mick Ireland was re-elected as mayor in the fourth round of a four-candidate race. Both city council incumbents were defeated in the two-seat RCV election in which nine candidates participated. The winners were selected after RCV tallies. 168 [[spoiled ballot]]s were recast by voters alerted to errors by their optical scanning machine.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = IRV passes first test |work= AspenTimes.com\n| accessdate = 2010-05-26\n| url = http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20090508/DAILYCOMMENT/905079943\n}}</ref> The city reported 0% invalid ballots in the mayor's race and 0.9% invalid ballots in the two-seat city council elections.<ref>[http://www.aspenpitkin.com/apps/news/news_item_detail.cfm?NewsItemID=1067]{{dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe elections were close, and some Aspen observers argued that a traditional runoff system would have given more time to consider their top choices. There also was debate over how to implement audit procedures.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aspen's May election under review |publisher=AspenTimes.com |accessdate=2009-08-18 |url=http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20090727/NEWS/907279983/1058}}</ref> In 2009 voters rejected an advisory measure to maintain IRV<ref>{{cite web |title=Aspen voters to vote on how they vote \u2014 again |publisher=AspenTimes.com |accessdate=2009-08-18 |url=http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20090722/NEWS/907219970&parentprofile=search}}</ref> and in 2010 approved a binding amendment to return to a traditional runoff system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aspendailynews.com/section/home/137464 |title=Instant runoff voting loses by razor-thin margin &#124; Aspen Daily News Online |website=Aspendailynews.com |date=2009-11-04 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aspendailynews.com/section/home/143505 |title=City voters repeal IRV &#124; Aspen Daily News Online |website=Aspendailynews.com |date=2010-11-03 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n====Basalt====\nThe city of [[Basalt, Colorado]] adopted RCV in 2002 for mayoral elections in which there are at least three candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colocode.com/basalt/basalt_00a.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723120817/http://www.colocode.com/basalt/basalt_00a.pdf |archivedate=July 23, 2008 }}</ref> The city is ready to run ranked-choice elections, but the elections in 2004, 2008, 2012 and 2016 did not have more than two candidates file for the mayor's office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20080301/NEWS/299002697/0/FRONTPAGE |title=It's six (and one) for Basalt town election |website=AspenTimes.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208003946/http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20080301/NEWS/299002697/0/FRONTPAGE |archive-date=2012-02-08 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref>\n\n====Telluride====\nOn November 4, 2008, voters in the town of [[Telluride, Colorado]], passed an ordinance with 67% of the vote to adopt RCV for the next three mayoral elections, starting in November 2011 if three candidates file for the office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telluride-co.gov/docs/ballot_issues_and_questions_nov_4_2008.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 6, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325012803/http://www.telluride-co.gov/docs/ballot_issues_and_questions_nov_4_2008.pdf |archivedate=March 25, 2009 }}</ref> The system was used for the city's 2011 mayoral election. The incumbent mayor Stu Fraser was re-elected by securing a majority of first choices.<ref>{{cite web|last=Klingsporn |first=Katie |url=http://www.telluridenews.com/articles/2011/11/09/news/doc4eba292a15de5179099885.txt |title=Stu Fraser wins mayoral race - Telluride Daily Planet: News |website=Telluridenews.com |date=2011-11-09 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In the 2015 mayoral election, Sean Murphy handily won an open seat election for mayor after trailing in first choices.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.telluridenews.com/news/article_dca80332-82cc-11e5-a470-377e9b752f32.html |title=Sean Murphy elected new mayor of Telluride - Telluride Daily Planet: News |website=Telluridenews.com |date=2015-11-04 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Florida===\n====Sarasota====\nThe city of [[Sarasota, Florida]] passed RCV (78%) in November 2007. While initially precluded from implementation by the lack of compatible voting machines, in 2015, new compatible machines were purchased by the Sarasota County Supervisor of Elections. Implementation now hinges on the adoption of certification criteria for ranked-choice voting tabulation equipment by the Florida Department of State's Division of Elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarasotagov.com/insidecitygovernment/content/cac/PDF/Elections/07-4719.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211063744/http://www.sarasotagov.com/InsideCityGovernment/Content/CAC/PDF/Elections/07-4719.pdf |archivedate=December 11, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarasotagov.com/insidecitygovernment/content/cac/Elections/Election%20Results%2011-6-07%20IRV.mht |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 11, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217060539/http://www.sarasotagov.com/InsideCityGovernment/Content/CAC/Elections/Election%20Results%2011-6-07%20IRV.mht |archivedate=December 17, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20071107/NEWS/711070307 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205070003/http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20071107/NEWS/711070307 |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/news/20180310/sarasota-city-commission-seeks-more-information-about-ranked-choice-voting | title=Sarasota City Commission seeks more information about 'ranked choice voting'}}</ref>\n\n===Maine===\n====Portland====\n {{main|Portland, Maine mayoral election, 2011}}\nIn November 2010, voters in [[Portland, Maine]], adopted a charter amendment with 52% to establish a directly elected mayor, using RCV. The first election was in November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/portland-returns-to-electing-its-mayor_2010-11-03.html |title=Portland returns to electing its mayor - The Portland Press Herald / Maine Sunday Telegram |website=Pressherald.com |date=2010-11-03 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Fifteen candidates ran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandvotes123.com |title=Home |website=PortlandVotes123 |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> The winner, Michael Brennan, led with 27% of first choices and won decisively in the final instant runoff voting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Koenig |first=Seth |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2011/11/09/news/portland/brennan-to-become-portland%E2%80%99s-first-popularly-elected-mayor-in-88-years/ |title=Brennan to become Portland's first popularly elected mayor in 88 years \u2014 Portland \u2014 Bangor Daily News \u2014 BDN Maine |website=Bangordailynews.com |date=2011-11-09 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Brennan ran for re-election against two opponents and was defeated by Ethan Strimling, who won a majority of votes in the first round. In November 2019, Strimling was defeated by Kate Snyder, who won by 62% to 38% over Spencer Thibodeau in the final instant runoff.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schroeder |first=Nick |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2019/11/05/news/portland/kate-snyder-on-track-to-unseat-ethan-strimling-in-portland-mayoral-race/|title=Kate Snyder unseats Ethan Strimling in Portland mayoral race|website=Bangordailynews.com |date=2019-11-05 |accessdate=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Portland city council in November 2019 voted unanimously to place a charter amendment on the March 2020 ballot to extend use of RCV to all city elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmtw.com/article/portland-voters-to-decide-expansion-of-ranked-choice-voting/29838136|title=Portland voters to decide expansion of ranked-choice voting|website=wmtw.com |date=2019-11-19 |accessdate=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\n===Maryland===\n====Takoma Park====\nThe city of [[Takoma Park, Maryland]] adopted RCV for city council and mayoral elections in 2006 after voters approved it with 84% support in November 2005.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.fairvote.org/assessing-instant-runoff-voting-in-takoma-park-md- |title=Assessing Instant Runoff Voting in Takoma Park (MD) |work=FairVote.org |date= March 28, 2007|accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007 the first RCV election was held to fill a city council vacancy in a three-way race with a majority winner in the first round. Voters selected Reuben Snipper with 107 votes (52.7%), defeating Eric Hensal with 72 votes (35.5%) and Alexandra Qu\u00e9r\u00e9 Barrionuevo with 23 votes (11.3%) and one write-in. Snipper said the possibility of using the RCV system changed the race's dynamics. \"I had every reason to believe this was going to be a close race,\" he said. \"It meant that when I knocked on a door, if a person indicated they were going to vote for another candidate, I didn't just leave right away. I tried to persuade them I would be a good second choice.\"<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/07/AR2007020700985.html Takoma Park's New Vote System Makes Debut], Miranda S. Spivack, [[Washington Post]], Feb. 8, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn November 2007 the mayor ran unopposed, and, out of six ward seats on the ballot, one was contested. Runoff provisions were not exercised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takomaparkmd.gov/clerk/election/2007/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108071833/http://www.takomaparkmd.gov/clerk/election/2007/index.html |archivedate=January 8, 2008 }}</ref> In November 2009, the mayor and one city councilor each faced one opponent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.net/stories/11032009/montnew235723_32572.shtml |title=Williams retains mayor's seat in Takoma Park |website=Gazette.net |date=2009-11-03 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In November 2011, one city council race drew three candidates; it was won by a candidate securing a majority of first choices.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gazette.net/article/20111108/NEWS/711089928/1124/1124/full-preliminary-results-shows-two-takoma-park-races-still-undecided%26template%3Dgazette |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-03 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120903172910/http://www.gazette.net/article/20111108/NEWS/711089928/1124/1124/full-preliminary-results-shows-two-takoma-park-races-still-undecided&template=gazette |archive-date=2012-09-03 |url-status = bot: unknown}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, the Ward Five race again was vacant. In another three-way race, first-time candidate Jarrett Smith was elected. After securing 44% of first choices, Smith won a majority in subsequent rounds against Eric Hensal.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jared |last=Gay |url=http://www.fairvote.org/instant-runoff-voting-in-action-in-takoma-park-3 |title=Instant Runoff Voting in Action in Takoma Park |work=FairVote.org |date=2012-07-18 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nRCV was used in regularly scheduled city elections in 2013, 2015 and 2017, along with a special election that required two rounds of counting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fairvote.org/research-and-analysis/blog/fairvote-survey-shows-support-for-takoma-park-voting-reforms/ |title=Survey Shows Support for Takoma Park Voting Reforms |work=FairVote.org  |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Massachusetts===\n\n==== Cambridge ====\n[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] has been using RCV for city council and school board since 1940.<ref name=\"bgm\" /> It is the only location in the US that uses the multi-member version of RCV, also known as [[single transferable vote]], which allows for more proportional representation. Six other Massachusetts towns were using the system by 1947, but all except Cambridge abandoned it due to concerns about Communists being elected.<ref name=\"bgm\">{{cite web |publisher=Boston Globe Magazine |author=Jessie Scanlon |date=17 Oct 2018 |title=Could Maine's new ranked-choice voting change American elections? |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2018/10/17/could-maine-new-ranked-choice-voting-change-american-elections/6VqNC73bQzMrPd0RSepA8L/story.html}}</ref>\n\n==== Amherst ====\n[[Amherst, Massachusetts]] adopted RCV in 2018 as part of a new town charter. The details of implementation were delegated to a Ranked Choice Voting Commission, with expected first use in November 2021 for the town council, school committee, and library trustees. All of these races will be in multi-member districts, varying from two to six members. <ref name=\"AmherstRCVCommission\">{{cite web |title=Ranked-Choice Voting Commission |url=https://www.amherstma.gov/3466/Ranked-Choice-Voting-Commission |publisher=Town of Amherst |accessdate=2019-12-30}}</ref> <ref name=\"AmherstCharter\">{{cite web |title=Amherst Home Rule Charter |url=https://www.amherstma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/41987/Amherst-Home-Rule-Charter |publisher=Town of Amherst |accessdate=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n==== Easthampton ====\n[[Easthampton, Massachusetts]] voted to adopt RCV for mayoral and city council elections in 2019 with 55% in favor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampshire-county/ranked-choice-voting-among-ballot-questions-for-easthampton-voters/|title=Easthampton residents vote \"yes\" for ranked-choice voting for mayor, council|date=2019-11-06|website=WWLP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n===Michigan===\n====Ann Arbor: city mayor, 1974\u20131976====\nRCV was adopted for mayoral races in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] in 1974 after a successful ballot initiative sponsored by the local [[Human Rights Party (United States)|Human Rights Party]]. RCV was used in the 1975 mayoral election. Democratic Party nominee [[Albert H. Wheeler]], the city's first African-American mayor, won after trailing the Republican incumbent 49% to 40% in the first round of counting, with remaining votes cast for the Human Rights Party nominee.<ref>Jonathan Marwil, ''A History of Ann Arbor'' (Ann Arbor: University of Michigan Press, 1990), 164\u2013165.</ref>\n\nIn April 1976, 62% of voters voted to repeal RCV in a special election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.migreens.org/hvgreens/aa-irv01.htm|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208053837/http://migreens.org/hvgreens/aa-irv01.htm|archivedate=February 8, 2012|url-status = dead|accessdate=June 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== Eastpointe ====\n[[Eastpointe, Michigan]] entered a consent decree with the US Department of Justice to implement RCV for city council elections for at least four years starting in 2019 to address claims of racial discrimination. Multi-winner RCV in the form of the [[single transferable vote]] is used, with two city council members elected at each staggered election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairvote.org/_eastpointe_michigan_to_become_first_in_state_to_implement_ranked_choice_voting|title=Eastpointe, Michigan to become first in state to implement ranked choice voting|last=FairVote.org|website=FairVote|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/justice-department-reaches-agreement-city-eastpointe-michigan-under-voting-rights-act|title=Justice Department Reaches Agreement with City of Eastpointe, Michigan, Under the Voting Rights Act|date=2019-06-05|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\n====Ferndale====\nThe city of [[Ferndale, Michigan]] passed (68%) RCV in 2004, however the system has not been implemented.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailytribune.com/stories/110304/loc_electbox03001.shtml |title=Results at a glance |date=November 3, 2004|publisher=Daily Tribune |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120100250/http://dailytribune.com/stories/110304/loc_electbox03001.shtml |archivedate=2008-01-20 |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytribune.com/government-and-politics/20130930/irv-whats-missing-from-ferndales-election |title=IRV: What's missing from Ferndale's election}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota===\n====Minneapolis====\nThe city of [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], passed (65%) RCV in November 2006.<ref>[http://www.startribune.com/10134/story/787059.html Measure to overhaul municipal races passes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102143705/http://www.startribune.com/10134/story/787059.html |date=2007-11-02 }}, Terry Collins, [[Star Tribune]], November 8, 2006.</ref> Although a citizen group filed a lawsuit in 2007 challenging the constitutionality of the system and to block its implementation,<ref>[https://archive.is/20130127000619/http://www.kare11.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=490380 Lawsuit challenges Minneapolis instant runoff voting system], 12/20/07 (Group filing lawsuit: [http://www.mnvoters.org/IRV.htm Minnesota Voters Alliance])</ref> the lawsuit was dismissed in a ruling on January 13, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ballot-access.org/2009/01/13/minnesota-state-court-rules-in-favor-of-instant-runoff-voting/ |title=Minnesota State Court Rules in Favor of Instant-Runoff Voting &#124; Ballot Access News |website=Ballot-access.org |date=2009-01-13 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> The [[Minnesota Supreme Court]] unanimously upheld this ruling in an opinion<ref>[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?q=766+NW+2d+683&hl=en&as_sdt=2006&case=16206935944988867912&scilh=0 Minnesota Voters Alliance v. City of Minneapolis], 766 N.W.2d 683 (Minn. 2009)</ref> on June 11, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brandt |first=Steve |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/local/47774887.html?elr=KArksi8cyaiUjc7YUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUU |title=Minneapolis will use ranked-choice voting method |website=StarTribune.com |date=2009-06-12 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2009, the City used RCV to elect the mayor, 13 city council seats, and seven other local offices and used a multi-seat variation of RCV, the [[single transferable vote]], for park board elections.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brandt |first=Steve |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/local/51361872.html?elr=KArksD:aDyaEP:kD:aUq9_b9b_jEkP:QUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUU |title=List of filers for Minneapolis city offices now complete |website=StarTribune.com |date=2009-07-22 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In November 2013, it again used RCV for those same elections, including in the open seat for the [[2013 Minneapolis mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sophia.stkate.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1022&context=maol_theses |format=PDF |title=Ranked Choice Voting in Minneapolis 2013 Elections |first=Erica L. |last=Mauter |website=Sophia.stkate.edu |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==== St Louis Park ====\n[[St. Louis Park, Minnesota]] began using RCV in November 2019 after adopting it in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fairvotemn.org/news/saint-louis-park-becomes-latest-us-city-adopt-ranked-choice-voting|title=Saint Louis Park Becomes Latest U.S. City to Adopt Ranked Choice Voting|date=2018-04-16|website=Fair Vote Minnesota|language=en|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\n====Saint Paul====\nOn November 4, 2009, voters in the city of [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]], passed a charter amendment with 52% of the vote to adopt RCV for future elections for mayor and city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stpaul.betterballotcampaign.org/node/1585 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 20, 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725065501/http://stpaul.betterballotcampaign.org/node/1585 |archivedate=July 25, 2011 }}</ref> In February 2011, the city council adopted rules governing the November 2011 elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/115685049.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 12, 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212212252/http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/115685049.html |archivedate=February 12, 2011 }}</ref> RCV elections took place for city council races, with two council races requiring multiple rounds of counting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olson |first=Rochelle |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/133581068.html |title=Ranked voting gets first runoff test |website=StarTribune.com |date=2011-11-09 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nRCV was used in St. Paul's 2013 election for mayor and in an open seat election for city council.<ref name=\"fairvote1\"/> RCV was also used for city council elections in 2015, including one election decided after multiple rounds.<ref name=\"fairvote.org\">{{cite web|first= Drew Spencer |last=Penrose |url=http://www.fairvote.org/research-and-analysis/blog/seven-ways-ranked-choice-voting-is-empowering-voters-in-2015/ |title=Seven Ways Ranked Choice Voting is Empowering Voters in 2015 |work=FairVote.org |date=2015-11-04 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===New Mexico===\n====Santa Fe====\nOn March 4, 2008, the city of [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]], passed a referendum for RCV by a vote of 5659 to 3044 (65% for).<ref>[https://www.santafenm.gov/media/files/city_clerk/March_4_2008_ELECTION_RESULTS.pdf \"Regular Municipal Election \u2013 March 4, 2008\"], City of Santa Fe.</ref> RCV was authorized to begin with the regular municipal election in March 2010 or as soon as equipment was available at a reasonable price.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120805151222/http://www.santafenm.gov/index.asp?nid=1204 \"Regular Municipal Election \u2013 March 2, 2010\"], City of Santa Fe.</ref> Responding to a petition to force the city to implement RCV, the [[New Mexico Supreme Court]] ordered RCV to be used in municipal elections, beginning with the March 6, 2018 races for mayor and city council.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1116919/supreme-court-clears-way-for-ranked-choice-voting-in-santa-fe.html |title=Supreme Court clears way for ranked-choice voting in Santa Fe |first1=T.S. |last1=Last |first2=Mark |last2=Oswald |newspaper=Albuquerque Journal |date=January 9, 2018 |access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref>\n\n====Las Cruces====\nFollowing successful implementation of RCV in Santa Fe, the city council of [[Las Cruces, New Mexico]] voted in June 2018 to adopt RCV, beginning with the November 2019 municipal elections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/local_news/second-city-in-new-mexico-opts-for-ranked-choice/article_4e8927df-44b3-5d14-a99d-61f6b2becc1a.html|title=Second city in New Mexico opts for ranked-choice|last=Stelnicki|first=Tripp|date=2018-06-04|work=The Santa Fe New Mexican|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===New York===\n====New York City====\nOn November 5, 2019, New York City voters passed Ballot Question #1 to amend the City Charter to \"Give voters the choice of ranking up to five candidates in primary and special elections for [[Mayor of New York City|Mayor]], [[New York City Public Advocate|Public Advocate]], [[New York City Comptroller|Comptroller]], [[New York City Comptroller|Borough President]], and [[New York City Council|City Council]] beginning in January 2021.\"<ref name=\"RCV officially adopted in NYC\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.charter2019.nyc/finalreport |title=Final Report |publisher=2019 New York City Charter Revision Commission |date=August 2, 2019}}</ref> In its October endorsement, ''The New York Times'' editorial board wrote: \"Ranked-choice voting is a smart, tested reform that would help New Yorkers elect candidates who have support from a majority of voters. Isn\u2019t that what democracy is all about?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/15/opinion/new-york-ranked-choice-voting.html |title=New Yorkers Have a Chance to Remake How They Vote |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===North Carolina===\nA 2006 law established that RCV would be used when judicial vacancies were created between a primary election and sixty days before a general election. In The law also established a pilot program for RCV for up to 10 cities in 2007 and up to 10 counties for 2008; to be monitored and reported to the 2007-2008 General Assembly.<ref>[http://www.ncleg.net/Sessions/2005/Bills/House/HTML/H1024v7.html House Bill 1024], [[General Assembly of North Carolina]], Session 2005.</ref>  In November 2010, [[North Carolina]] had three RCV elections for local-level [[North Carolina Superior Court|superior court]] judges, each with three candidates, and [[North Carolina judicial elections, 2010#Court of Appeals (Wynn seat)|a statewide IRV election]] for a [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]] seat (with 13 candidates). The Court of Appeals race is believed to be the first time RCV has been used in any statewide general election in the United States.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=http://www.democracy-nc.org/news/blog/2010/08/10/tuesday-august-10-2010/ |title=Tuesday, August 10, 2010 \u00ab Democracy North Carolina Blog |website=Democracy-nc.org |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170009/http://www.democracy-nc.org/news/blog/2010/08/10/tuesday-august-10-2010/ |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status = dead|df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbar.org/about/communications/news/2010-news-articles/race-for-wynns-seat-requires-instant-runoff-voting.aspx |title=North Carolina Bar Association News & Events &#124; NCBA News |website=Ncbar.org |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nSeveral municipalities considered participating in the RCV pilot in 2007. Cary, Hendersonville and Kinston voted to participate; Kinston dropped out because there were not enough candidates running to use RCV. Other cities declined to participate in the pilot. No North Carolina counties volunteered to participate in RCV in the 2008 elections held in conjunction with state and federal races.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.citizen-times.com/blogs/index.php?blog=10&title=no_instant_runoff_this_year |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708043244/http://blogs.citizen-times.com/blogs/index.php?blog=10&title=no_instant_runoff_this_year |url-status = dead|archive-date=2012-07-08 |title=CITIZEN-TIMES: Capital Letters - Post details: No instant-runoff this year |website=Blogs.citizen-times.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01 }}</ref> In August 2008 the governor signed legislation extending the pilot program for local elections to be held in 2009-2011.<ref>[http://www.citizen-times.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=200880804060]{{dead link|date=August 2009}}</ref>\n\nThere was much debate whether RCV was successful when it was used.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carynews.com/news/story/8057.html |title=Opinion mixed on Cary's instant-runoff trial |first=Adam |last=Arnold |date=Jan 22, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080203232045/http://www.carynews.com/news/story/8057.html |archivedate=2008-02-03 |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbc17.com/midatlantic/ncn/search.apx.-content-articles-NCN-2007-10-30-0028.html|title=Critics Take Runoff Concerns To Elections Board - Search - NBC 17|date=2008-05-18|access-date=2020-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518071413/http://www.nbc17.com/midatlantic/ncn/search.apx.-content-articles-NCN-2007-10-30-0028.html|archive-date=2008-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://instantrunoff.blogspot.com/2010/07/don-frantz-only-person-elected-by.html|title=Instant Runoff Voting in the United States: Don Frantz, the only person elected by instant runoff voting in NC speaks out|date=2010-07-17|website=Instant Runoff Voting in the United States|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> This debate continued in the North Carolina legislature when it debated legislation to extend the pilot program.<ref>[http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/gascripts/BillLookUp/BillLookUp.pl?Session=2007&BillID=S1263 Senate Bill 1263], [[General Assembly of North Carolina]], Session 2007-8</ref> Some verified voting advocates contended that the RCV tabulation procedures used were not legal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncvoter.net:80/irv.html|title=Instant Runoff Voting|last=|first=|date=2016-04-30|website=NC Coalition for Verified Voting|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430145853/http://www.ncvoter.net/irv.html|archive-date=2016-04-30|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncvoter.net/instant-runoff-voting-regrets-in-nc/|title=Instant Runoff Voting Regrets in NC|date=2016-08-29|website=NC Voter|language=en|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://irvbad4nc.blogspot.com/2008/08/instant-runoff-messing-up-north.html|title=Instant Runoff: Messing Up North Carolina Elections and Efforts to Reduce the Damage ~ Protect North Carolina Elections - Stop Instant Runoff Voting|last=Mccloy|first=Joyce|date=2008-08-17|website=Instant Runoff|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Both advocates and opponents of the provision supported amendments to the pilot program to: ensure that the local governing body of any jurisdiction participating in the pilot must approve their participation; the jurisdiction must develop and implement voter education plans; and the [[University of North Carolina]] School of Government must approve procedures for conducting RCV elections by January 2009. After these amendments were adopted, the state House of Representatives, by a majority of 65-47, rejected an amendment designed to remove the pilot program from the legislation, and the legislation ultimately won approval by both houses.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/gascripts/BillLookUp/BillLookUp.pl?Session=2007&BillID=S1263&votesToView=all |title=North Carolina General Assembly - Senate Bill 1263 Information/History (2007-2008 Session) |website=Ncga.state.nc.us |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Hendersonville again used RCV,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/politics/story/1518353.html |title='Patient's bill' also boon to chiropractors, therapists |first1=Benjamin |last1=Niolet |first2=Ryan Teague |last2=Beckwith |newspaper=The News & Observer  |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=2009-08-26 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511160222/http://www.newsobserver.com/politics/story/1518353.html |archivedate=May 11, 2009 }}</ref> while the Cary Town Council voted to use a traditional runoff method.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.wral.com/news/news_briefs/story/5060298/ |title=Cary votes to keep current election method |website=WRAL.com |date=2009-04-30 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> Three candidates ran for mayor in Hendersonville in November 2009; five candidates ran for two seats on the city council using a multi-seat version of RCV.<ref>[http://www.hendersoncountync.org/elections/cont_cand_rpt_3g.pdf]{{dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref> All seats were filled based on first choices without the need for further counting.<ref>[http://www.blueridgenow.com/article/20091103/NEWS/910299988/1151?Title=Volk-Smith-Collis-win-Hendersonville-election]{{dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Hendersonville's city council unanimously voted to use RCV a third time, although ultimately not enough candidates filed for office to trigger the need for the system.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harbin |first=John |url=http://www.blueridgenow.com/article/20110408/NEWS/110409860/1016/OPINION02?Title=Hendersonville-votes-to-keep-instant-runoff-ballots |title=Hendersonville votes to keep instant runoff ballots |website=BlueRidgeNow.com |date=2011-04-08 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe RCV pilot program was repealed by the General Assembly in 2013 as part of a sweeping [[voter ID]] bill, meaning that special judicial elections with more than two candidates would once again be decided by a simple plurality.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n====Cary====\nIn October 2007 the city of [[Cary, North Carolina]] used RCV for municipal election for three council seats and for mayor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/news/local/politics/story/1906539/|title=Polls Close; Turnout Light in Local Elections|last=WRAL|date=2007-10-09|website=WRAL.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> The mayor's race (with two candidates) and two of the council seats (with four and three candidates on the ballot) were won with a majority in the first round. The remaining council seat, with three candidates, went to a second round of counting; the plurality winner in the first round went on to win with 50.9% of the final round vote, amounting to 46.4% of first-round ballots cast, with 8.9% of the ballots offering no preference between the top two candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wakegov.com/elections/results.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080111111349/http://www.wakegov.com/elections/results.htm |archivedate=January 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ COUNCIL MEMBER C-B 1<br />CARY MUNICIPAL DISTRICT B:\n!Candidate\n!colspan=2|Round 1\n!colspan=2|Round 2\n|- align=right\n!Don Frantz\n|<span style=\"color:red;\">'''1151'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''(38.1%)'''</span>\n|<span style=\"color:red;\">'''1401'''</span>||<span style=\"color:red;\">'''(46.4%)'''</span>\n|- align=right\n!Vickie Maxwell\n|1075||(35.6%)\n|1353||(44.8%)\n|- align=right\n!Nels Roseland\n|793||(26.2%)\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|--\n|- align=right\n!Other\n|3||(0.0%)\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|--\n|- align=right\n!Exhausted ballots\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|--\n|268||(8.9%)\n|- align=right\n!Total\n|3022||(100%)\n|3022||(100%)\n|}\n\nCary used hand or machine-marked paper ballots that are read on optical scanners manufactured by ES&S. First column choices were tallied at the precinct. The second and third column choices were counted at a central location.\n\n===Oregon===\n====Benton County====\nOn November 8, 2016, voters in [[Benton County, Oregon]], passed a charter amendment with 54.3% of the vote to enact RCV for county elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.co.benton.or.us/elections/page/nov-8-2016-general-election-results-and-turnout|accessdate=November 13, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The first use of RCV will take place in November 2020, after the state legislature in 2018 appropriated funds to enable the county to administer the elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.betterballotbenton.com/|title=Better Ballots for Benton|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114011853/http://www.betterballotbenton.com/|archive-date=2016-11-14|accessdate=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee===\n====Memphis====\nOn November 4, 2008, voters in the city of [[Memphis, Tennessee]], passed a charter amendment with 71% of the vote to enact RCV for city elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shelbyvote.com/scVote/dotShowDoc/scvote/electionResults/content/electionResults.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 6, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108042548/http://www.shelbyvote.com/scVote/dotShowDoc/scvote/electionResults/content/electionResults.htm |archivedate=November 8, 2008 }}</ref> The first use of RCV has been dependent on the city's ability to administer the election: it was scheduled for 2019, however, the city council voted in 2017 to place a referendum to repeal RCV on the 2018 ballot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.memphisflyer.com/NewsBlog/archives/2017/12/05/city-council-votes-to-repeal-instant-runoff-voting|title=City Council Votes to Repeal Instant Runoff Voting|last=Smith|first=Maya|work=Memphis Flyer|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en}}</ref> 63% of voters elected to keep RCV but it remains unclear when it will be implemented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commercialappeal.com/story/news/2018/11/07/instant-runoff-voting-memphis-shelby-county-midterm-election/1858041002/|title=Instant runoff voting survives at the polls, but will it be implemented in Memphis?|website=The Commercial Appeal|language=en|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\n===Utah===\n\nIn 2018, Utah passed a law allowing municipalities to opt in to RCV voting starting with 2019 municipal elections.<ref name=\"bgm\" /> Six cities opted in to use RCV in 2019, [[West Jordan, Utah|West Jordan]], [[Vineyard, Utah|Vineyard]], [[Salem, Utah|Salem]], [[Cottonwood Heights, Utah|Cottonwood Heights]], [[Lehi, Utah|Lehi]], and [[Payson, Utah|Payson]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldextra.com/news/opinion/herald-editorials/herald-editorial-ranked-choice-voting-may-be-a-winner-for/article_ee79d44c-e181-5aa1-8b3e-66f8819a40a1.html|title=Herald editorial: Ranked-choice voting may be a winner for voters|last=Board|first=Daily Herald Editorial|website=Daily Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref> but only Vineyard and Payson will be following through with the trial, with the others waiting to see how it is implemented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/payson-vineyard-will-pilot-ranked-choice-voting-for-state/article_333d3def-c1a9-53ee-b8d0-525769309e0b.html|title=Payson, Vineyard, will pilot ranked choice voting for state|last=England|first=Katie|date=|website=Daily Herald|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Vermont===\n\n==== Burlington mayor, 2005\u20132010 ====\n{{see also|Burlington, Vermont mayoral election, 2009}}The city of [[Burlington, Vermont]] approved RCV for use in mayoral elections with a 64% vote in 2005.<ref>[http://www.burlingtonvotes.org/faq 4. How did this change to IRV come about?] ''Over 64% of Burlington voters voted in favor of the IRV Charter amendment in March, 2005, and it went into effect on May 12, 2005, when the governor signed the ratification bill, H.505, which had been passed by both the House and Senate.''</ref>  The 2006 Burlington mayoral race was decided after two rounds of tallying, and the mayoral race in 2009 was decided in three rounds. Unlike Burlington's first RCV mayoral election in 2006, the RCV winner in 2009 ([[Vermont Progressive Party|VT Progressive]] candidate [[Bob Kiss]]) was neither the same as the [[plurality voting system|plurality]] winner ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate Kurt Wright) nor the [[Condorcet method|Condorcet]] winner ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate Andy Montroll).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vermontdailybriefing.com/?p%3D1215 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 30, 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726125759/http://vermontdailybriefing.com/?p=1215 |archivedate=July 26, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangevoting.org/Burlington.html |title=Burlington Vermont 2009 IRV mayoral election |website=RangeVoting.org |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe results caused a post-election controversy regarding the RCV method.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vermontdailybriefing.com/?p=1213|title=Voting Paradoxes and Perverse Outcomes: Political Scientist Tony Gierzynski Lays Out A Case Against Instant Runoff Voting|last=Baruth|first=Philip|date=March 12, 2009|publisher=Vermont Daily Briefing|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726125814/http://vermontdailybriefing.com/?p=1213|archivedate=July 26, 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref> In late 2009, a group of several Democrats (who supported Republican Kurt Wright) led a signature drive to force a referendum on RCV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cctv.org/watch-tv/programs/one-person-one-vote-press-conference|title=One Person, One Vote Press Conference|last=|first=|date=2009-12-29|website=CCTV Center for Media and Democracy|language=en|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref> According a local columnist, the vote was a referendum on Mayor Kiss, who was a \"lame duck\" because of a scandal relating to [[Burlington Telecom]] and other local issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/vermont/burlington-residents-seek-repeal-of-instant-runoff-voting/Content?oid=2177125|title=Burlington Residents Seek Repeal of Instant Runoff Voting|last=Totten|first=Shay|date=|work=Seven Days|access-date=2018-04-08|language=en}}</ref> However, in an interview with [[Vermont Public Radio]], Mayor Kiss disputed that claim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vprarchive.vpr.net/vpr-news/bob-kiss-on-irv-burlington-telecom-and-the-moran-plant/|title=Bob Kiss on IRV, Burlington Telecom And The Moran Plant - VPR Archive|website=vprarchive.vpr.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref> RCV was repealed in March 2010 by a vote of 52% to 48%.<ref name=\"repeal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wcax.com/story/12074080/burlington-voters-repeal-irv|title=Burlington voters repeal IRV|last=|first=|date=March 2, 2010|website=|publisher=[[WCAX-TV|Wcax.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409132306/http://www.wcax.com/story/12074080/burlington-voters-repeal-irv|archive-date=2016-04-09|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rutlandherald.com/article/20100427/NEWS03/4270339/1004/NEWS03 |title=Instant run-off voting experiment ends in Burlington : Rutland Herald Online |website=Rutlandherald.com |date=2010-04-27 |accessdate=2016-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055602/http://www.rutlandherald.com/article/20100427/NEWS03/4270339/1004/NEWS03 |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/burlingtonfreepress/access/1975028861.html?FMT=ABS | work=The Burlington Free Press | first=John | last=Briggs | title=Instant runoff rejected | date=March 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe repeal reverted the system back to a 40% rule that requires a top-two runoff if no candidate exceeds 40% of the vote. Had the 2009 election occurred under these rules, Kiss and Wright would have advanced to the runoff. If the same voters had participated in the runoff as in the first election and not changed their preferences, Kiss would have won the runoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ci.burlington.vt.us/ct/elections/irv/|title=City of Burlington, Vermont {{!}} Instant Runoff Voting|last=|first=|date=2011-09-28|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928110147/http://www.ci.burlington.vt.us/ct/elections/irv/|archive-date=2011-09-28|access-date=2018-04-08}} - FAQ 5. for IRV: Under the old [pre-IRV] system a candidate could be elected with just over 40% of the vote, meaning a candidate could win even though seen as the last choice of nearly 60% of the voters.</ref> In 2011, an initiative effort to increase the winning threshold from the 40% plurality to a 50% majority failed.\n\n===Washington===\n\n==== Pierce County, 2006\u20132009 ====\n[[Pierce County, Washington]], passed (53%) RCV in November 2006 for most of its county offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piercecountywa.org/pc/abtus/ourorg/aud/elections/rcv.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109164811/http://www.piercecountywa.org/pc/abtus/ourorg/aud/elections/rcv.htm |archivedate=January 9, 2008 }}</ref> Voters upheld the 2008 implementation timing with a vote of 67% in 2007 and made minor adjustments to the charter language involving ballot access and numbers of rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.pierce.wa.us/pc/abtus/ourorg/aud/elections/misc/currentresults.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 27, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080208222430/http://www.co.pierce.wa.us/pc/abtus/ourorg/aud/elections/misc/currentresults.htm |archivedate=February 8, 2008 }}</ref> Seven RCV elections took place on November 4, 2008 and one on November 3, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.pierce.wa.us/pc/abtus/ourorg/aud/elections/RCV/ranked/rcvresults.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 6, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108063824/http://www.co.pierce.wa.us/pc/abtus/ourorg/aud/elections/RCV/ranked/rcvresults.htm |archivedate=November 8, 2008 }}</ref> The introduction of RCV was marked by controversies about costs and confusion about the simultaneous introduction of the [[nonpartisan blanket primary|top two election system]] following a Supreme Court ruling that restored it after it passed statewide in 2004, but was struck down by courts in 2005. On November 3, 2009, voters repealed RCV.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/story/940959.html|title=Voters Changing their Minds on Ranked-Choice|last=Wickert|first=David W.|date=2009-11-09|work=Tacoma News Tribune|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=July 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n== Legislation ==\n\n=== Bills in current session ===\nThe table below lists all state bills containing provisions that would enact Ranked-Choice Voting for certain elections held within the respective state. Pilot Program refers to legislation which allows cities, towns, and counties to opt-in to Ranked-Choice Voting for their respective elections.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n\n! style=\"width:130px\" | State\n! Elections affected\n! Type\n! Session\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:90px\"| Bill\n! Latest Action\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Lower House\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Upper House\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Executive\n! Status\n\n|-\n\n| {{flag|Hawaii}}\n| Special federal elections; special elections for vacant county council seats\n|\n| 2019-20\n| SB 2006<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/HI/bill/SB2006/2020|title=SB 2006|last=|first=|date=|website=Legiscan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| Feb 28, 2020\n| \n| {{yes|Passed 24 - 1}}{{efn|name=MN|This bill originally provided that it take effect \"immediately upon passage.\" However, the start date was later changed to 2050 in committee.}}\n| \n| Pending\n\n|-\n\n| {{flag|Virginia}}\n| Municipal\n| Pilot Program\n| 2020\n| HB 1103<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?201+sum+HB1103|title=HB 1103|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia General Assembly|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| Feb 25, 2020\n| {{yes|Passed 57 - 42}}\n| {{yes|Passed 22 - 18}}\n| {{yes|Signed}}\n| {{yes|Becomes Law in July 1, 2021}}\n\n|-\n\n| {{flag|Virginia}}\n| State, Federal\n| Mandatory\n| 2020\n| HB 360<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?201+sum+HB360|title=HB 360|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia State Legislature|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| Jan 31, 2018\n| {{Pending|Delayed to 2021}}\n| \n|\n| Pending\n\n|}\n\n===Bills receiving floor votes in previous sessions===\n<!-- NOTICE: When you update this section, please update the \"passed\" list at the very top of the article! -->\nThe table below lists past bills that received a floor vote (a vote by the full chamber) in at least one chamber of the state's legislature. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"<!--Please do not include bills that did not receive a floor vote-->\n\n|-\n\n! style=\"width:130px\"|State\n! Elections affected\n! Type\n! Session\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:90px\"| Bill\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Lower house\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Upper house\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Executive\n! Outcome\n\n|-\n\n|{{flag|California}}\n| Cities, counties and local education agencies\n| \n| 2019-20\n| SB 212 \n| {{yes|Passed 56\u201318}}\n| {{yes|Passed 29\u20139}}\n| {{no|Vetoed}}\n| {{no|Failed}}\n\n|-\n\n|{{flag|Utah}}\n| Municipal\n| Pilot\n| 2019-20\n| HB 277 \n| {{yes|Passed 64\u20132}}\n| {{yes|Passed 26\u20133}}\n| {{yes|Signed}}\n| {{yes|Law}}\n\n|}\n\n==Absentee use==\nSeveral states jurisdictions that hold runoff elections allow certain categories of absentee voters to submit ranked-choice ballots, because the interval between votes is too short for a second round of absentee voting. Ranked-choice ballots enable long-distance absentee votes to count in the runoff election if their first choice does not make the runoff. [[Alabama]], [[Arkansas]], [[Mississippi]], [[Louisiana]] and [[South Carolina]] used ranked-choice ballots for overseas voters in 2014 and in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|first=Drew Spencer |last=Penrose  |url=http://www.fairvote.org/research-and-analysis/blog/proven-innovations-to-uphold-voting-rights-for-overseas-voters/ |title=Proven Innovations to Uphold Voting Rights for Overseas Voters |work=FairVote.org  |date= |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> A city using this practice is [[Springfield, Illinois]] after voters approved it with 91% support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electionline.org/Portals/1/Publications/SC.EAP.2006primary.pdf |title=Initiatives \u2013 Pew Center on the States |publisher=Electionline.org |date= |accessdate=6 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516235221/http://www.electionline.org/Portals/1/Publications/SC.EAP.2006primary.pdf |archivedate=16 May 2008 |df= }}</ref>  Louisiana uses it also for out-of-state members of the United States military and others who reside overseas.<ref>{{Citation\n| title    =IRV for Louisiana's [sic] Overseas Voters\n| type    =web page \n| publisher =FairVote IRV America \n| url =http://archive.fairvote.org/?page=1669\n| accessdate  =June 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Implementations rejected==\nBetween 1912 and 1930, limited forms of RCV (typically with only two rankings<ref name=\":0\" />) were implemented and subsequently repealed in the states of [[Florida]], [[Indiana]], [[Maryland]], [[Minnesota]], and [[Wisconsin]]. In the 1970s, it was implemented and repealed in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref name=\":1\" />  More recently, it was adopted and repealed in [[Pierce County, Washington]] (2006-2009);<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Burlington, Vermont]] (2005-2010);<ref name=\":3\" /> and [[Aspen, Colorado]] (2007-2010);<ref name=\":4\" /> and in North Carolina, which allowed its use in elections between 2006 and 2013. \n\nAccording to [[FairVote]], an organization advocating RCV, dozens of states have entertained RCV legislation since 2000. In 2008, Republican [[Vermont]] governor [[Jim Douglas]] vetoed legislation which would have established RCV for that state's congressional elections starting that year<ref>Kinzel, Bob, [http://www.vpr.net/news_detail/80010/douglas-vetoes-two-election-bills/ \"Douglas vetoes two election bills\"], Vermont Public Radio, April 4, 2008. Retrieved 2016-11-12.</ref> despite testimony in support by Vermont's independent U.S. Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fairvote.org/?page=1998 |title=FairVote - Bernie Sanders: Testimony to the Vermont Senate Government Operations Committee  |website=Archive.fairvote.org |date=2007-03-15 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> and its Democratic U.S. House Member [[Peter Welch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.fairvote.org/?page=1999 |title= Peter Welch: Testimony to the Vermont Senate Government Operations Committee  |website=Archive.fairvote.org |date=2007-03-15 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> In 2003, an amendment to the [[California State Constitution]] was proposed with wide-ranging goals of [[election reform]], including RCV for statewide offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://info.sen.ca.gov/pub/bill/sen/sb_0001-0050/sca_14_bill_20030912_introduced.html |title=Unindexed archive directory |accessdate=January 28, 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041012070428/http://info.sen.ca.gov/pub/bill/sen/sb_0001-0050/sca_14_bill_20030912_introduced.html |archivedate=October 12, 2004 }}</ref> In the [[Washington (state)|state of Washington]], an initiative seeking to adopt RCV in 2005 failed to garner enough signatures. The city of [[Vancouver, Washington]] voted in 1999 to adopt RCV and the state legislature enacted enabling legislation in 2004, but the city in 2006 chose not to exercise its option. RCV for all state and federal elections was on [[Alaska]]'s statewide ballot in August 2002, when it was defeated. It also was defeated by voters in [[Glendale, Arizona]] in 2008, in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]] in 2011, and in [[Duluth, Minnesota]] in 2015.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\t \n== Proposed federal laws ==\nIn the U.S. Congress, the Voter Choice Act of 2005<ref>{{cite web|first=Cynthia |last=McKinney |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h109-2690 |title=Voter Choice Act of 2005 (2005; 109th Congress H.R. 2690) |website=GovTrack.us |date=2005-05-26 |accessdate=2016-04-01}}</ref> sought to require the use of RCV for general elections for federal office. The [[For the People Act of 2019]], passed by the House of Representatives, promotes the purchase of voting systems capable of RCV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ivn.us/2019/03/03/ranked-choice-voting-finds-its-way-to-the-floor-of-the-us-house/|title=Ranked Choice Voting Finds Its Way to the Floor of the US House|date=2019-03-03|website=IVN.us|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> The [[Fair Representation Act]] supports amending several laws including the [[Help America Vote Act]] and the [[Reapportionment Act of 1929]] to mandate the conversion of all congressional districts from single- to multi-member districts elected by ranked-choice voting as well as the creation of state-level nonpartisan [[redistricting commission]]s for congressional redistricting.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oHRPMJmzBBw Explainer video: How does ranked-choice voting work?], Minnesota Public Radio MPR.org\n*[https://ballotpedia.org/Ranked-choice_voting_(RCV) Ballotopedia: \"Ranked Choice Voting\"]\n\n{{Voting rights in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Instant-Runoff Voting In The United States}}\n[[Category:Instant-runoff voting]]\n[[Category:Electoral reform in the United States]]\n[[Category:Federal elections of the United States]]\n[[Category:Local elections in the United States]]\n[[Category:Primary elections in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Chad The Goatman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegislation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranked-choice_voting_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "List of Emmerdale characters (2019)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Emmerdale'' characters (2019)}}\n''[[Emmerdale]]'' is a British soap opera first broadcast on 16 October 1972. The following is a list of characters that appear during 2019, by order of first appearance. All characters are introduced by the series producers Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/news/a855492/emmerdale-three-new-producers/|title=Emmerdale confirms three new producers as Iain MacLeod's exit sparks major changes|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=24 April 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref> The first character to be introduced is [[#Vinny|Vinny]] (Bradley Johnson), the son of [[Mandy Dingle]] ([[Lisa Riley]]), followed by [[#Bear Wolf|Bear Wolf]] (Joshua Richards), the father of [[Paddy Kirk]] ([[Dominic Brunt]]), in February. [[#Will Taylor|Will Taylor]] ([[Dean Andrews]]), the father of [[Dawn Taylor (Emmerdale)|Dawn Taylor]] (Olivia Bromley), and [[#Nate Robinson|Nate Robinson]] (Jurell Carter), a farmhand, were introduced in April. [[Jamie Tate]]'s (Alexander Lincoln) family, consisting of wife [[#Andrea Tate|Andrea Tate]] (Anna Nightingale) also played paula in 1995 episode of emmerdale as nick bates date and daughter [[#Millie Tate|Millie Tate]] (Willow Bell), made their debuts in June. [[#Wendy Posner|Wendy Posner]] ([[Susan Cookson]]), the mother of [[#Lee Posner|Lee Posner]] (Kris Mochrie), first appears in July, followed by [[#Al Chapman|Al Chapman]] ([[Michael Wildman]]) the father of [[Ellis Chapman (Emmerdale)|Ellis Chapman]] (Asan N'Jie) in August. September features the introductions of [[#Danny Harrington|Danny Harrington]] (Louis Healy) and [[#Derek|Derek]] ([[Tommy Cannon]]) in guest stints. Additionally, multiple [[#Other characters|other characters]] were featured during the year.\n\n== Vinny ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series = Emmerdale\n|name = Vinny\n|portrayer = Bradley Johnson\n|introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n|first = Episode 8358<br />{{Start date|2019|1|4|df=y}}\n|last = \n|years= 2019\u2013\n|classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters|Present; regular]]\n|occupation = \n|home = Wishing Well cottage\n<!--Please do not add relatives that have not shared storylines with him, or do not hold any notable significance per WP:SOAPS. -->\n|father= [[Paul Ashdale]]\n|stepmother= [[Mandy Dingle]]\n}}\n'''Vinny''', played by Bradley Johnson, first appears on 4 January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Emmerdale airs Mandy Dingle's return \u2013 has she brought Paddy Kirk's son with her? |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25750593/emmerdale-spoilers-mandy-dingle-lisa-riley-paddy-kirk-son-vinny/ |accessdate=4 January 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=4 January 2019}}</ref> The character and Johnson's casting details were announced on 28 December 2018.<ref name=\"Vinnie\">{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Emmerdale star Lisa Riley reveals Mandy Dingle's big return storyline |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25696088/emmerdale-spoilers-lisa-riley-mandy-dingle-return-storyline/ |accessdate=29 December 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=28 December 2018}}</ref> Vinny is introduced as the 16-year-old son of [[Mandy Dingle]] ([[Lisa Riley]]), who returns after a 17-year absence, having lived in [[Southampton]] with her son.<ref name=\"Vinnie\"/> Riley explained that Vinny is similar to Mandy, creating \"a lot of scope\" and big stories.<ref name=\"Vinnie\"/> The actress praised Johnson and enjoyed working with him, describing the prospect of Vinny's future stories as exciting.<ref name=\"Vinnie\"/>\n\nSince Mandy had sex with her former husband [[Paddy Kirk]] ([[Dominic Brunt]]) before leaving in 2001, it is suggested that he could be Vinny's father. Allison Jones of ''[[Inside Soap]]'' predicted that the identity of Vinny's father could \"blow the Dingles apart\".<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite magazine |last1=Jones |first1=Allison |title=Mandy comes home... and all hell breaks loose! |magazine=[[Inside Soap]] |date=5-11 January 2019 |volume=2019 |issue=1 |pages=4\u20137}}</ref> When Paddy meets Vinny, he does not question if he could be his son. Brunt confirmed that the writers had not decided how to conclude the story.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> [[Lucy Pargeter]], who portrays Paddy's partner [[Chas Dingle]], thought that Vinny's paternity could \"go in any direction\" and could have implications for Paddy's relationship with her son [[Aaron Livesy|Aaron Dingle]] ([[Danny Miller (actor)|Danny Miller]]).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Anderton |first1=Joe |title=Emmerdale stars tease whether Paddy Kirk has a secret son with Mandy Dingle |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25698734/emmerdale-stars-tease-paddy-kirk-secret-son-mandy-dingle/ |accessdate=29 December 2018 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhen Vinny discovers that [[Samson Dingle]] (Sam Hall) has [[Pawn shop|pawned]] a wedding ring that belonged to Samson's dead mother, Vinny covers for him so that [[Sam Dingle]] ([[James Hooton]]) is not upset. When Sam threatens to throw Vinny out, Samson reveals that it was him. Upon confiding in Sam, Samson and [[Lydia Hart (Emmerdale)|Lydia Hart]] (Karen Blick), he reveals that Mandy is not his birth mother, but his stepmother, and that [[Paul Ashdale]] ([[Reece Dinsdale]]) is his father.\n\nVinny departed in the episode broadcast on 8 January 2019.<ref name=\"Kilkelly\">{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=7 ways Emmerdale has set up a second return for Lisa Riley as Mandy Dingle |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25801815/emmerdale-spoilers-mandy-dingle-second-return-teasers/ |accessdate=8 January 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=8 January 2019}}</ref> Following his exit, Daniel Kilkelly of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' described Vinny as \"bumbling and awkward\" and thought he resembled Paddy, believing the character's parentage would be a good storyline in the future.<ref name=\"Kilkelly\"/> Kilkelly enjoyed Johnson's portrayal of Vinny and thought that there was scope for Vinny to be \"a great character in his own right\", adding that the soap was missing \"a comic young male presence\" following the death of [[Gerry Roberts]] (Shaun Thomas).<ref name=\"Kilkelly\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Bear Wolf ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series = Emmerdale\n|name = Bear Wolf\n|portrayer = Joshua Richards\n|years=2019\u2013\n|introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n|first = Episode 8391<br />{{Start date|2019|2|12|df=y}}\n|last = \n|classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|occupation = Wrestler\n|sons = [[Paddy Kirk]]\n|granddaughters= [[#Pregnancy|Grace Dingle]]<br>[[#Eve Dingle|Eve Dingle]]\n}}\n'''Bear Wolf''', Otherwise known as \"Edward\" played by Joshua Richards, first appears in February 2019.<ref name=\"Bear\"/> The character was referenced on-screen during January 2019 episodes, where it was suggested that he could be the father of [[Paddy Kirk]] ([[Dominic Brunt]]) following an affair with Paddy's mother.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mehmedova |first1=Filiz |title=Emmerdale reveals Mandy Dingle is still keeping secrets as she says her goodbyes to the village |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25803909/emmerdale-mandy-dingle-secret-village-exit-vinny-paddy-kirk/ |accessdate=15 January 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=8 January 2019}}</ref> Richards' casting details were announced on 15 January 2019.<ref name=\"Bear\">{{cite news |last1=Harp |first1=Justin |title=Emmerdale casts Joshua Richards as Paddy Kirk's possible dad Bear Wolf |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25896662/emmerdale-casts-paddy-kirk-dad-bear-wolf-joshua-richards/ |accessdate=15 January 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=15 January 2019}}</ref> Bear is introduced when Paddy's partner, [[Chas Dingle]] ([[Lucy Pargeter]]), and friend, [[Marlon Dingle]] ([[Mark Charnock]]), encourage him to meet him in [[Belfast]] at a wrestling convention.<ref name=\"Bear\"/> He is billed as a \"ageing pro wrestler\".<ref name=\"Bear\"/> Multiple members of the ''Emmerdale'' cast filmed scenes in Northern Ireland for Bear's introduction.<ref name=\"Bear\"/> Richards expressed his delight at joining the cast and filming in Yorkshire. He added that Bear is \"a great character\".<ref name=\"Bear\"/> Series producer Kate Brooks also expressed her excitement at Richards' casting, commenting, \"An actor of immense talent and charisma, he's a brilliant addition to the ''Emmerdale'' team.\"<ref name=\"Bear\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Will Taylor ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series = Emmerdale\n|name = Will Taylor\n|portrayer = [[Dean Andrews]]\n|introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n|years = 2019\u2212\n|first = Episode 8449<br />{{Start date|2019|4|17|df=y}}\n|last = \n|classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|occupation = Habitual offender\n<!--Please do not add relatives that have not shared storylines with him, or do not hold any notable significance per WP:SOAPS. -->\n|daughters = [[Dawn Taylor (Emmerdale)|Dawn Taylor]]\n|grandsons = Lucas\n}}\n\n'''Will Taylor''', portrayed by [[Dean Andrews]], first appears on 17 April 2019.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 8449|series=Emmerdale|serieslink=Emmerdale|credits=Series producers: Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw; Director: David Beauchamp; Writer: Andrew Kirk|network=[[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]|airdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> Andrews' casting details were announced on 21 January 2019,<ref name=\"Andrews\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Jess |title=Emmerdale casts Life on Mars star Dean Andrews as mystery new character |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a25976253/emmerdale-casting-dean-andrews-cain-dingle/ |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> but further details about the character, including his name, were embargoed until his first appearance.<ref name=\"Will\">{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Emmerdale star Dean Andrews speaks out after Harriet Finch stalker reveal |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a27182117/emmerdale-spoilers-dean-andrews-will-taylor-harriet-finch-stalker/ |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=17 April 2019}}</ref> Will is the father of established character [[Dawn Taylor (Emmerdale)|Dawn Taylor]] (Olivia Bromley) and the former husband of [[Harriet Finch]] (Katherine Dow Blyton), who was an undercover police officer during her marriage to Will and assisted in his arrest.<ref name=\"Will\"/> The character is also introduced as a rival for [[Cain Dingle]] ([[Jeff Hordley]]).<ref name=\"Andrews\"/> Andrews expressed his delight at joining the cast of ''Emmerdale'', which [[executive producer]] Jane Hudson also reiterated. She praised his performances and teased that he would \"shake things up\" for some characters.<ref name=\"Andrews\"/> Andrews later admitted that he found it hard to keep his role a secret and looked forward to exploring the character.<ref name=\"Will\"/>\n\nPrior to his introduction, Harriet began being tormented by an unknown person. When Dean arrives, it emerges that Will is the tormenter and he and Dawn are working together to get revenge on Harriet for sending Will to prison.<ref name=\"Andrews\"/> Andrews told Daniel Kilkelly of ''Digital Spy'' that Will is resentful towards Harriet for sending him to prison, partly because it meant he became estranged from Dawn. The actor wanted to explore Will's emotional state.<ref name=\"Andrews\"/> Dow Blyton observed that Harriet does not expect to see Will again and explained that Will and Dawn \"want her to suffer as much as they have; they want to ruin her life.\"<ref name=\"Houghton\">{{cite news |last1=Houghton |first1=Rianne |title=Emmerdale star Katherine Dow Blyton teases the big moment Harriet Finch faces her stalker |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a27125690/emmerdale-spoilers-harriet-finch-confronts-stalker-katherine-dow-blyton-reveals/ |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=12 April 2019}}</ref> The actress added that Harriet would try to \"reach out\" to Will after discovering he is responsible because she naturally seeks the best in people.<ref name=\"Houghton\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Nate Robinson ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series = Emmerdale\n|name = Nate Robinson\n|portrayer = Jurell Carter\n|introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n|years = 2019\u2013\n|first = Episode 8457<br />{{Start date|2019|4|25|df=y}}\n|last = \n|classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|occupation = Farmhand\n|mother = [[Cara Robinson]]\n|father = [[Cain Dingle]]\n|stepmother = [[Moira Barton]]\n|halfsisters = [[Debbie Dingle]]\n|halfbrothers = [[Kyle Winchester]]<br />[[Isaac Dingle]]\n|grandfathers = [[Zak Dingle]] \n|grandmothers = [[Faith Dingle]]\n|nieces = [[Sarah Sugden (2005 character)|Sarah Sugden]]\n|nephews = [[Jack Sugden (2012 character)|Jack Sugden]]\n|aunts = [[Chas Dingle]] <br> [[Belle Dingle]]\n|uncles = [[Sam Dingle]]\n|cousins = [[Aaron Livesy]] <br> [[Samson Dingle]]<br> [[#Eve Dingle|Eve Dingle]]<br>[[Charity Dingle]]<br>[[Noah Dingle]]<br>[[Mandy Dingle]]\n}}\n'''Nate Robinson''', portrayed by Jurell Carter, made his first appearance on 25 April 2019. The character was introduced during the Big Night Out week of episodes, where he shares a kiss with [[Rhona Goskirk]] ([[Zoe Henry]]).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Emmerdale introduces mystery man Nate Robinson in Big Night Out episodes|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a27273668/emmerdale-spoilers-nate-robinson-jurell-carter/ |accessdate=9 July 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=25 April 2019}}</ref> He later secures a job working on [[Moira Barton|Moira Dingle]]'s ([[Natalie J. Robb]]) farm and pursues a relationship with [[Amy Wyatt]] (Natalie Ann Jamieson). He later begins a sexual affair with Moira behind Amy and [[Cain Dingle]]'s ([[Jeff Hordley]]) backs. After Cain learns of the affair, he takes Moira and Nate out on a boat to confront them. As he and Nate fight, Nate reveals that he is Cain's son.\n{{-}}\n\n== Andrea Tate ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Emmerdale\n| name = Andrea Tate\n| portrayer = Anna Nightingale\n| introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n| years = 2019\u2212\n| first = Episode 8493<br />{{Start date|2019|6|3|df=y}}\n| last = \n| classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n| occupation = \n| home = Home Farm\n| husband = [[Jamie Tate]]\n| daughters = [[#Millie Tate|Millie Tate]]\n}}\n'''Andrea Tate''', played by [[Anna Nightingale]], first appears on 3 June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Emmerdale \u2013 who is Andrea Tate and show newcomer Anna Nightingale? |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a27654465/emmerdale-cast-spoilers-andrea-tate-anna-nightingale/ |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=30 May 2019}}</ref> The character and Nightingale's casting details were announced on 28 May 2019.<ref name=\"Groome\">{{cite news |last1=Groome |first1=Imogen |title=Emmerdale spoilers: Jamie Tate's secret family revealed as Kim makes a new enemy |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/05/28/emmerdale-spoilers-jamie-tates-secret-family-revealed-as-kim-makes-a-new-enemy-9598230/ |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=28 May 2019}}</ref> Andrea is introduced as the wife of [[Jamie Tate]] (Alexander Lincoln), alongside their daughter [[#Millie Tate|Millie Tate]] (Willow Bell).<ref name=\"Groome\"/> She also becomes a new rival for Jamie's mother, [[Kim Tate]] ([[Claire King]]).<ref name=\"Family\"/> Lincoln billed Andrea as fiery, \"less innocent than Jamie\", and protective of Jamie.<ref name=\"Family\"/> He added that Andrea is not as \"manipulative\" as Kim, but she will \"not [...] take any nonsense from [Kim]\".<ref name=\"Family\"/> Nightingale also teased her character's romantic side, describing her as \"a harmless flirt [who] loves her husband\".<ref name=\"Andrea\"/> Lincoln thought Andrea's characterisation made her an \"interesting\" character.<ref name=\"Family\"/> Nightingale enjoyed working with her on-screen family and hoped that writers would place Andrea in friendships with [[Leyla Harding]] ([[Roxy Shahidi]]), [[Tracy Metcalfe]] ([[Amy Walsh (actress)|Amy Walsh]]), [[Rhona Goskirk]] ([[Zoe Henry]]) and [[Priya Sharma]] ([[Fiona Wade]]).<ref name=\"Andrea\"/> Imogen Groome, writing for the ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'', predicted that Andrea's arrival would create \"some explosive drama\".<ref name=\"Groome\"/>\n\nPrior to the character's introduction, she was not referenced; Lincoln explained that Jamie does not mention his wife because he \"wanted to keep his wife and daughter away from everyone in the village\".<ref name=\"Lincoln\"/> Andrea and Jamie's marriage is strained upon her arrival as he has ignored her attempts at contact in the previous weeks. Lincoln did not believe that Jamie intentionally ignored his family, but also pointed out that Jamie failed to tell Andrea about what he was doing in the village.<ref name=\"Lincoln\"/> Jamie wants Andrea and Millie to relocate to the village, so gets Andrea a job and moves the family into Home Farm, which Lincoln said would create \"a bit of conflict\".<ref name=\"Lincoln\"/>\n\nIn their fictional backstory, Andrea and Jamie have been married for five years and met at university in [[Liverpool]].<ref name=\"Lincoln\">{{cite news |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Emmerdale star Alexander Lincoln explains Jamie Tate's secret family twist |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a27616287/emmerdale-spoilers-alexander-lincoln-jamie-tate-family-twist/ |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=29 May 2019}}</ref> It soon emerges that after Kim asked [[Graham Foster (2017 character)|Graham Foster]] ([[Andrew Scarborough]]) to look after Jamie when she was imprisoned, Graham employed Andrea to do the job, having met her in a local bar.<ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite news |last1=Debnath |first1=Neela |title=Emmerdale spoilers: How do Andrea Tate and Graham Foster know each other? |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1139187/Emmerdale-spoilers-Andrea-Tate-Graham-Foster-Kim-Claire-King-Jamie-ITV-soap |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=11 June 2019}}</ref> However, when Andrea fell in love with Jamie, she cut contact with Graham and he had not seen her since.<ref name=\"Graham\"/> Nightingale noted that when she and Graham meet again, Andrea understands that her disappearance has \"reprecussions\".<ref name=\"Andrea\"/> She also pointed out that Graham is a \"pretty terrifying\" character who Andrea should be afraid of.<ref name=\"Andrea\"/>\n\nAndrea clashes with Kim after scaring one of her horses, leaving Jamie \"stuck in the middle of some awkward conversations\".<ref name=\"Groome\"/> Kim is surprised to discover that Jamie has a family, which does not ease the tension between Andrea and Kim. Lincoln observed that Kim thinks \"Jamie can do much better\".<ref name=\"Family\">{{cite magazine |last1=Tyler |first1=Laura-Jayne |title=Jamie's secret family! |magazine=[[Inside Soap]] |date=1-7 June 2019 |volume=2019 |issue=22 |pages=8\u20139}}</ref> Due to Jamie and Kim's estranged relationship, Andrea does not expect him to be close with his mother.<ref name=\"Lincoln\"/> Lincoln thought that Andrea was \"annoyed\" by Kim's presence in Jamie's life considering their history,<ref name=\"Family\"/> but Nightingale explained that although Andrea feels \"secure\" in her marriage, she is also \"cautious\" of Kim.<ref name=\"Andrea\">{{cite magazine |last1=Jones |first1=Allison |title=Mysterious girl! |magazine=[[Inside Soap]] |date=8-14 June 2019 |volume=2019 |issue=23 |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> Lincoln added that Jamie becomes \"stuck between these women\" as they both want the best for him.<ref name=\"Family\"/> Laura-Jayne Tyler of ''Inside Soap'' predicted \"plenty of spiky showdowns between [Andrea] and her overbearing mother-in-law!\"<ref name=\"Andrea\"/>\n\n== Millie Tate ==\n<!--{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Emmerdale\n| name = Millie Tate\n| portrayer = Willow Bell\n| introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n| years = 2019\u2212\n| first = Episode 8493<br />{{Start date|2019|6|3|df=y}}\n| last = \n| classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Recurring and guest characters|Present; recurring]]\n| occupation = Student\n| home = Home Farm\n| father = [[Jamie Tate]]\n| mother = [[#Andrea Tate|Andrea Tate]]\n| grandmothers = [[Kim Tate]]\n}}-->\n'''Millie Tate''', played by Willow Bell, first appears on 3 June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waterfall |first1=Sarah |title=Emmerdale spoilers: Jamie Tate has a secret wife and child! Kim will flip! |url=https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/events/emmerdale-spoilers-jamie-tate-secret-wife/ |accessdate=11 August 2019 |work=[[What's on TV]] |date=28 May 2019}}</ref> The character and Bell's casting details were announced on 28 May 2019.<ref name=\"Groome\"/> Willow is introduced as the five-year-old daughter of established character [[Jamie Tate]] (Alexander Lincoln) and [[#Andrea Tate|Andrea Tate]] (Anna Nightingale), the latter of whom she is introduced with.<ref name=\"Groome\"/><ref name=\"Lincoln\"/> Lincoln billed Millie as \"a bossy one\" who further complicates Jamie's life.<ref name=\"Family\"/> Writers did not mention Millie and Andrea prior to their introduction to create a surprise for the audience when they discovered Jamie had a family.<ref name=\"Family\"/> Millie and her family move into the Home Farm estate, where Jamie's estranged mother, [[Kim Tate]] ([[Claire King]]), lives. Lincoln explained that Jamie wants Millie to grow up in the village.<ref name=\"Lincoln\"/> Kim struggles with Millie's existence as she did not expect to be a grandmother. On this, Lincoln commented, \"Kim really doesn't like being called grandma. She hates it!\"<ref name=\"Family\"/>\n\n== Wendy Posner ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Emmerdale\n| name = Wendy Posner\n| portrayer = [[Susan Cookson]]\n| introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n| years = 2019\u2212\n| first = Episode 8521<br />{{Start date|2019|7|1|df=y}}\n| last = \n| classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters|Present; regular]]\n| occupation = Nurse\n| home = \n| sons = [[#Lee Posner|Lee Posner]]<br>[[#Luke Posner|Luke Posner]]\n| grandsons = [[List of Emmerdale characters (2020)#Harry Sugden|Harry Sugden]]\n}}\n'''Wendy Posner''', played by [[Susan Cookson]], first appears on 1 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Koncienzcy |first1=Rebecca |title=ITV viewers spot Coronation Street actress in Emmerdale |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/tv/itv-viewers-spot-coronation-street-16516122 |accessdate=12 August 2019 |work=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=1 July 2019}}</ref> The character and Cookson's casting details were announced on 19 June 2019.<ref name=\"Wendy\">{{cite news |title=Susan Cookson joins Emmerdale |url=https://www.femalefirst.co.uk/tv/news/susan-cookson-joins-emmerdale-1199490.html |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=Female First |date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Wendy is introduced as the mother of [[#Lee Posner|Lee Posner]] (Kris Mochrie), who is the rapist of [[Victoria Barton]] ([[Isabel Hodgins]]).<ref name=\"Wendy\"/> Cookson expressed her delight at joining the cast and called Wendy \"a fantastic character\" with \"gritty and emotional storylines\".<ref name=\"Wendy\"/> Jane Hudson, the soap's [[executive producer]], called Cookson a \"fabulous addition to the cast\" and looked forward to the character's introduction.<ref name=\"Milan\">{{cite news |last1=Milan |first1=Aidan |title=Who is Susan Cookson who plays Lee's mum Wendy Posner on Emmerdale? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/02/who-is-susan-cookson-who-plays-wendy-posner-on-emmerdale-10102521/ |accessdate=12 August 2019 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=2 July 2019}}</ref> Cookson previously appeared in ''Emmerdale'' in 1993, 1997 and 2003 as minor characters.<ref name=\"Wendy\"/>\n\nThe character is billed as \"indignant\" by ''[[Inside Soap]]''.<ref name=\"Hell\">{{cite magazine |last1=Jones |first1=Allison |title=Fresh hell for Victoria! |magazine=[[Inside Soap]] |date=29 June - 5 July 2019 |volume=2019 |issue=26 |pages=8\u20139}}</ref> Wendy arrives to confront Victoria about the rape allegations, which she claims are false.<ref name=\"Milan\"/> Hodgins explained that when Wendy arrives, Victoria is \"shock and scared\" because Wendy is the \"enemy\".<ref name=\"Hell\"/> The actress pointed out that Wendy has Lee's interests \"at heart\".<ref name=\"Hell\"/> Wendy leaves when [[Charity Dingle]] ([[Emma Atkins]]) confronts her.<ref name=\"Hell\"/> When Wendy returns the following day with Lee, they discover that Victoria is pregnant with Lee's baby. Hodgins told Allison Jones of ''Inside Soap'' that this is \"opening a can of worms that Victoria wanted to keep closed\".<ref name=\"Hell\"/> Victoria later agrees to speak to Wendy, who reveals that she wants a role in the child's life and suggests that Lee could go for custody of the baby.<ref name=\"Victoria\">{{cite magazine |last1=Jones |first1=Allison |title=Victoria: \"I'm leaving the village!\" |magazine=[[Inside Soap]] |date=6-12 July 2019 |volume=2019 |issue=27 |pages=6\u20137}}</ref> A show spokesperson noted that this is \"the worst scenario as far as Victoria is concerned\".<ref name=\"Victoria\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Al Chapman ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Emmerdale\n| name = Al Chapman\n| portrayer = [[Michael Wildman]]\n| introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n| years = 2019\u2212\n| first = Episode 8564<br />{{Start date|2019|8|13|df=y}}\n| last = \n| classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n| wife = [[Jessie Grant]] (backstory)\n| sons = [[Ellis Chapman (Emmerdale)|Ellis Chapman]]\n}}\n\n'''Al Chapman''', played by [[Michael Wildman]], first appears on 13 August 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hughes |first1=Johnathon |title=Who's playing Ellis's dad Al Chapman in Emmerdale? Where you've seen actor Michael Wildman before |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/soaps/emmerdale/2019-08-13/whos-playing-elliss-dad-al-chapman-in-emmerdale-where-youve-seen-actor-michael-wildman-before/ |accessdate=14 August 2019 |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=13 August 2019}}</ref> The character and Wildman's casting details were announced on 14 July 2019.<ref name=\"Al\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Susannah |title=Emmerdale casts Harry Potter star Michael Wildman as Ellis Chapman's father |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a28387757/emmerdale-cast-michael-wildman-ellis-chapman-father/ |accessdate=14 August 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Al is introduced as the estranged father of [[Ellis Chapman (Emmerdale)|Ellis Chapman]] (Asan N'Jie) and the former husband of [[Jessie Dingle]] (Sandra Marvin).<ref name=\"Al\"/> Wildman began filming on a regular contract in July 2019.<ref name=\"Al\"/> Wildman expressed his joy at joining the cast and was unsure about how well-received his character, who he called \"interesting\", would be.<ref name=\"Al\"/> Wildman and N'Jie also starred on ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'' together and N'Jie found the connection between their characters \"surreal\".<ref name=\"Dodds\">{{cite news |last1=Dodds |first1=Emma |title=Emmerdale newbie Michael Wildman already has a connection to his on-screen son |url=https://heatworld.com/entertainment/tv-movies/emmerdale-michael-wildman-al-chapman/ |accessdate=14 August 2019 |work=[[Heat (magazine)|Heat]] |date=6 August 2019}}</ref> Wildman previously performed a screen test for a different character, but was unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Al\"/>\n\nWildman billed the character as \"ambiguous\" and a \"judge of character\".<ref name=\"Al\"/> He explained that Al is manipulative and able to \"talk to five people at the same time and talk to them all in different ways\".<ref name=\"Al\"/> Al arrives to connect with Ellis and Wildman explained that Al \"thinks he can just come back in to his life and pick up where he left off\".<ref name=\"Al\"/> He noted that the character would arrive \"ruffling a few feathers\".<ref name=\"Al\"/> The actor added that Al quickly makes Jessie's husband, [[Marlon Dingle]] ([[Mark Charnock]]), feel \"insecure\".<ref name=\"Al\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Danny Harrington==\n<!--{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Emmerdale\n| name = Danny Harrington\n| portrayer = Louis Healy\n| introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n| years = 2019\n| first = Episode 8594<br />{{Start date|2019|9|16|df=y}}\n| last = Episode 8701<br />{{Start date|2020|1|9|df=y}}\n| classification = [[List of Emmerdale characters#Recurring and guest characters|Present; guest]]\n| occupation = Student\n}}-->\n'''Danny Harrington''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/jtsdfm/emmerdale--episode-8645/|title=Emmerdale \u2013 Episode 8645|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> played by Louis Healy, first appears on 16 September 2019.<ref name=\"Derek Danny\"/> The character and Healy's casting details were announced on 3 September 2019.<ref name=\"Derek Danny\">{{cite news |last1=Phillipson |first1=Daisy |title=Emmerdale announces two new characters arriving this month |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a28903295/emmerdale-announces-two-new-characters-september/ |accessdate=21 September 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=3 September 2019}}</ref> Danny is introduced as a love interest for teenage character [[Sarah Sugden (2005 character)|Sarah Sugden]] (Katie Hill).<ref name=\"Derek Danny\"/> Healy was contracted for a guest stint, which Tilly Pearce of the ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' confirmed would last a \"few months\".<ref name=\"Pearce\"/> The character, who is billed as a \"new boy-next-door\", will feature in a \"sinister\" storyline with Sarah.<ref name=\"Pearce\"/> As a result of spending time with Danny, Sarah soon neglects her studies, creating tension with her grandmother, [[Charity Dingle]] ([[Emma Atkins]]).<ref name=\"Healy\">{{cite news |last1=Hughes |first1=Johnathon |title=Emmerdale debut for Denise Welch and Tim Healy's son |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/soaps/emmerdale/2019-09-16/emmerdale-debut-for-denise-welch-and-tim-healys-son/ |accessdate=21 September 2019 |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=16 September 2019}}</ref> ''[[Radio Times]]''{{'}} Johnathon Hughes described Danny as the \"school heart-throb\".<ref name=\"Healy\"/> Pearce warned that Sarah should be cautious around Danny.<ref name=\"Pearce\">{{cite news |last1=Pearce |first1=Tilly |title=Emmerdale spoilers: Sinister storyline revealed for Sarah Sugden as Louis Healy joins soap |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/09/04/emmerdale-spoilers-sinister-storyline-revealed-for-sarah-sugden-as-louis-healy-joins-soap-10678596/ |accessdate=21 September 2019 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Derek ==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Emmerdale\n| name = Derek Malone\n| portrayer = [[Tommy Cannon]]\n| introducer = Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw\n| first = Episode 8597<br />{{Start date|2019|9|19|df=y}}\n| last = Episode 8606 <br/>{{End date|2019|9|30|df=y}}\n| classification = [[List of past Emmerdale characters#Last appeared in 2019|Former; guest]]\n}}\n'''Derek''', played by [[Tommy Cannon]], first appears on 19 September 2019.<ref name=\"Tommy\">{{cite news |last1=Hughes |first1=Johnathon |title=Tommy Cannon and 7 other comedy legends who made soap cameos |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/soaps/emmerdale/2019-09-19/tommy-cannon-and-7-other-comedy-legends-who-made-soap-cameos/ |accessdate=21 September 2019 |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=19 September 2019}}</ref> Cannon announced on [[Twitter]] in August 2019 that he would be appearing in ''Emmerdale'', but deleted his tweet shortly after.<ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Helen |title=Emmerdale spoilers: Tommy Cannon confirms he's joining ITV soap as mystery character |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1163267/Emmerdale-spoilers-Tommy-Cannon-Derek-ITV-soap-video |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=8 August 2019}}</ref> In the tweet, he expressed his delight at his casting. A show spokesperson declined to comment on Cannon's casting.<ref name=\"Kelly\"/> Further details about Cannon's casting and the character were announced on 3 September 2019.<ref name=\"Derek Danny\"/> Derek is introduced as a patient of established character [[Manpreet Sharma]] (Rebecca Sarker).<ref name=\"Derek Danny\"/> Cannon was contracted for a guest stint, which was billed to create \"serious consequences\" for other regular characters.<ref name=\"Derek Danny\"/> Cannon's casting was well received by the press and media and ''Emmerdale'' cast members congratulated him.<ref name=\"Kelly\"/>\n\nIt was later confirmed that Derek would be killed off at the conclusion of his stint, sparking a new story for the Sharma family.<ref name=\"Derek dead\"/> He dies from [[Salmonella poisoning]] after eating [[Rishi Sharma]]'s (Bhasker Patel) homemade chocolates, which also makes [[David Metcalfe]] ([[Matthew Wolfenden]]) ill. When Manpreet sorts Derek's belongings, she discovers a valuable stamp collection which could help the family's financial crisis.<ref name=\"Derek dead\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Jess |title=Emmerdale lines up new death storyline as the Sharmas and Dingles receive a shock |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a29202413/emmerdale-death-derek-storyline-sharmas-dingles/ |accessdate=26 September 2019 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]] |date=24 September 2019}}</ref> The character departed in episode 8606, originally broadcast on 30 September 2019.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Episode 8606|series=Emmerdale|serieslink=Emmerdale|credits=Series producers: Kate Brooks and Laura Shaw; Director: Ian Barber; Writer: Samantha Doland de Vaux|network=[[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]|airdate=30 September 2019}}</ref> Kyle O'Sullivan of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' dubbed Derek's death as \"gruesome\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Sullivan |first1=Kyle |title=Tommy Cannon's gruesome Emmerdale death leaves fans fearing David will be next |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/tommy-cannons-gruesome-emmerdale-death-20375042 |accessdate=17 January 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirrorr]] |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Others ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Character \n! scope=\"col\" | Date(s)  \n! scope=\"col\" | Actor \n! scope=\"col\" | Circumstances\n|- valign=\"top\"\n! scope=\"row\" | {{nowrap|'''Max Garrick'''}}{{Anchor|Max Garrick}}\n| {{nowrap|12 April\u201325 June}}\n| {{nowrap|Jordan Reece<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/emmerdale/a27123402/emmerdale-spoilers-billy-fletcher-max/|title=Emmerdale lines up a nasty shock for Billy Fletcher as newcomer Max arrives|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=12 April 2019|work=[[Digital Spy]]|